var e=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"renal_mass_eval","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/lectures/lectures.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Renal Mass Evaluation","category":"GU Pathology","summary":"A comprehensive journey from anatomy to molecular classification of kidney tumors.","body":"## Renal Mass Evaluation: Full Transcript\\n\\n**Introduction**\\nWelcome to the comprehensive guide on Renal Mass Evaluation. In this session, we will navigate the complex landscape of kidney tumors, which range from benign entities like Oncocytoma to highly aggressive cancers such as Renal Medullary Carcinoma. Our primary goal is to shift your thinking from simple labeling to a risk-stratification mindset. We will learn to connect the anatomic location—cortex versus medulla—to the likely diagnosis, use a morphology-first triage system to categorize tumors as \\"Clear,\\" \\"Pink,\\" or \\"Papillary,\\" and integrate molecular drivers like VHL and MiT family alterations into your diagnostic logic. Most importantly, we will focus on preventing clinical harm: avoiding the overtreatment of indolent mimics and ensuring aggressive tumors are not under-called.\\n\\n**Anatomic Context**\\nAnatomy is the foundation of staging. The renal cortex is the birthplace of most common RCC subtypes, whereas the medulla is a \\"red-alert\\" zone. Tumors centered here, such as Collecting Duct Carcinoma or Renal Medullary Carcinoma, are often high-grade and aggressive. Always verify the tumor's relationship to the capsule, perinephric fat, and renal vein, as these are critical staging parameters that define patient prognosis.\\n\\n**The Universe of Renal Tumors**\\nThe WHO classification groups renal tumors by a combination of morphology and molecular drivers. exist in distinct clusters. The clear cell lineage is dominated by VHL/HIF pathway alterations. The papillary spectrum is heterogeneous. The eosinophilic group presents the classic challenge of distinguishing benign Oncocytoma from malignant Chromophobe RCC. We also have specific \\"traps\\" like the Clear Cell Papillary Renal Cell Tumor, an indolent mimic that must not be confused with aggressive clear cell carcinoma. Remember your gatekeeper stains: PAX8 confirms renal origin, while CA9 and CK7 patterning helps split the difficult differentials.\\n\\n**Diagnostic Algorithm**\\nWhen approaching a renal mass, follow a disciplined sequence. First, check the location: is it medullary or cortical? Second, assess the dominant cytoplasmic quality. precise triage. For clear cells, the default is Clear Cell RCC, but stop if you see diffuse CK7 positivity or \\"cup-like\\" CA9 staining. For eosinophilic tumors, use CK7 to separate the scattered pattern of Oncocytoma from the diffuse pattern of Chromophobe RCC. Finally, never finalize a case without a prognostic audit: check for necrosis, sarcomatoid or rhabdoid differentiation, and venous invasion.\\n\\n**Deep Dive: Clear Cell RCC**\\nClear Cell RCC is the most common subtype, driven by 3p loss and VHL mutations. It presents with a classic delicate vascular network. The essential IHC profile is PAX8 positive, Vimentin positive, and the hallmark CA9 \\"box\\" pattern—diffuse membranous staining. If you see a \\"cup\\" pattern (basolateral only), stop; you are likely dealing with a mimic. Prognosis here is driven by stage and grade. Remember, Grade 4 is defined by extreme pleomorphism or sarcomatoid/rhabdoid change—features that override any \\"average\\" grade.\\n\\n**Critical Differential: The Clear Mimics**\\nClear Cell Papillary Renal Cell Tumor is a critical entity to recognize because it is indolent. Mislabeling it as conventional Clear Cell RCC leads to unnecessary cancer anxiety and surveillance. Morphologically, look for \\"piano-key\\" nuclei and tubulopapillary architecture. The IHC signature is the \\"flip\\": CK7 diffuse positive and CA9 \\"cup-like\\" positive. This contrasts sharply with the CK7 negative/patchy and CA9 \\"box\\" pattern of conventional Clear Cell RCC.\\n\\n**Deep Dive: The Pink Tumors**\\nThe distinction between Chromophobe RCC and Oncocytoma is a classic pathology dilemma. Oncocytoma is benign; Chromophobe RCC is malignant. Oncocytomas typically have scattered CK7 staining and may show central scars. Chromophobe RCCs often have \\"plant-like\\" cell borders, perinuclear halos, and show diffuse CK7 positivity. Reporting consequence: calling oncocytoma malignant causes overtreatment; calling chromophobe RCC benign can omit staging and follow-up.\\n\\n**Summary**\\nTo wrap up: Renal mass evaluation requires integrating morphology, anatomy, and molecular surrogates. Use PAX8 to confirm renal epithelial lineage; it does not subtype RCC. Use CA9 and CK7 patterns to split the mimics. And always, always report the adverse prognostic features—necrosis, grade 4 change, and invasion—that truly determine the patient's future.","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[{"type":"intro","title":"Welcome","content":"\\n## Approach to the Renal Mass\\n\\nKidney tumors range from benign entities like [[Oncocytoma]] to highly aggressive carcinomas like [[Renal Medullary Carcinoma]].\\n\\n**Learning Objectives**\\n- **Anatomy:** Relate location (cortex vs medulla vs pelvis) to likely subtype and staging implications.\\n- **Morphology-first triage:** “Clear” vs “Pink/Oncocytic” vs “Blue/Basophilic/Papillary.”\\n- **Prognostic thinking:** Stage + grade + necrosis + sarcomatoid/rhabdoid features drive outcomes (not just the label).\\n- **Molecular logic:** Connect phenotype to pathways (e.g., VHL/HIF; MiT family).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Clinical-risk mindset (what hurts patients if you’re wrong)\\n- **Overcall indolent mimics** → overtreatment + excessive surveillance.\\n- **Undercall aggressive patterns** (sarcomatoid/rhabdoid/venous invasion) → underestimated relapse risk.\\n- **Miss medullary high-grade tumors** → dangerous under-triage of urgency.\\n        ","config":{"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true}},{"type":"anatomy","title":"Anatomic Context","config":{"system":"gu"},"content":"\\n## The Genitourinary System\\n\\nAnatomic layering is staging logic:\\n\\n- **Cortex:** Typical origin of major RCC subtypes.\\n- **Medulla:** Red-alert origin zone for high-grade entities (e.g., [[Collecting Duct Carcinoma]], [[Renal Medullary Carcinoma]]).\\n- **Pelvis:** Think [[Urothelial Carcinoma]] (different staging + marker logic).\\n- **Capsule/Perinephric fat/Renal vein:** Where pT escalation happens.\\n\\n**High-stakes gross correlation**\\n- Confirm relationship to capsule and perinephric fat.\\n- Identify and sample renal sinus fat and renal vein margins.\\n- Map tumor to medulla vs cortex if borderline—this can change the diagnostic universe.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"The Universe of Renal Tumors","config":{"nodeId":"Clear Cell RCC","highlightGroup":"Kidney","entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Papillary RCC","Chromophobe RCC","Oncocytoma","Clear Cell Papillary","Translocation RCC","Collecting Duct Carcinoma","Renal Medullary Carcinoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Galaxy View: Renal Epithelial Tumors\\n\\nWHO5 renal tumors are defined by **morphology + molecular drivers**.\\n\\n**Key clusters (with prognostic tone)**\\n- **Clear cell lineage (VHL/HIF):** [[Clear Cell RCC]] — variable risk; stage/grade dominate.\\n- **Papillary spectrum:** [[Papillary RCC]] — heterogeneous; avoid “papillary pattern = papillary RCC” thinking.\\n- **Eosinophilic / oncocytic:** [[Chromophobe RCC]] vs [[Oncocytoma]] — major harm is mislabeling benign lesions as malignant (or vice versa).\\n- **Indolent mimic:** [[Clear Cell Papillary]] — specific overtreatment risk.\\n- **MiT family:** [[Translocation RCC]] — variable behavior; demands suspicion-based confirmation.\\n- **Medullary high-grade:** [[Collecting Duct Carcinoma]] / [[Renal Medullary Carcinoma]] — urgent aggressive biology signals.\\n\\n**Gatekeepers**\\n- [[PAX8]] confirms renal lineage; does **not** subtype.\\n- [[CA9]] patterning is biologic (HIF signaling): **Box vs Cup**.\\n- [[CK7]] patterning splits multiple branches (oncocytic and clear-cell mimics).\\n        "},{"type":"algorithm","title":"Diagnostic Algorithm","config":{"algorithmId":"algo_renal","entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Clear Cell Papillary","Translocation RCC","Papillary RCC","Oncocytoma","Chromophobe RCC","Collecting Duct Carcinoma","Renal Medullary Carcinoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Algorithmic Triage (morphology → discriminators → prognosis)\\n\\n### Step 0: “Where is it?” (cortex vs medulla vs pelvis)\\n- Medullary-centered + high grade → prioritize **CDC/RMC** differential; urgency and prognosis differ dramatically.\\n\\n### Step 1: Dominant cytoplasm\\n1) **Clear**\\n- Default: [[Clear Cell RCC]]\\n- Stop signs: CK7 diffuse, CA9 cup, young age, papillary architecture, psammoma bodies → consider [[Clear Cell Papillary]] or [[Translocation RCC]].\\n\\n2) **Eosinophilic / oncocytic**\\n- Default split: [[Oncocytoma]] vs [[Chromophobe RCC]]\\n- Core discriminator: CK7 **scattered** (oncocytoma) vs **diffuse** (chromophobe).\\n\\n3) **Basophilic / papillary**\\n- Consider [[Papillary RCC]] but **prove it** (exclude CCRCC with papillary areas and MiT RCC).\\n\\n### Step 2: Prognostic capture (don’t wait until the end)\\n- Stage cues: renal sinus fat, renal vein, perinephric fat.\\n- Grade cues (CCRCC/Papillary): nucleolar prominence; **grade 4 features override averages**.\\n- Adverse histology: necrosis, sarcomatoid/rhabdoid, venous invasion.\\n        "},{"type":"algorithm","title":"Mechanism-First Tree","config":{"algorithmId":"algo_renal_mechanism","entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Papillary RCC","Chromophobe RCC","Oncocytoma","Translocation RCC","Renal Medullary Carcinoma","Collecting Duct Carcinoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Mechanism-First Decision Tree\\n\\n**Concept:** Instead of just looking at the cells, ask *what biochemical system is broken?*\\n\\nThis tree guides you from molecular programs to specific diagnoses:\\n1.  **Renal Epithelial Lineage** (PAX8/WT1)\\n2.  **Oxygen Sensing & Hypoxia** (VHL-HIF axis)\\n3.  **Metabolic Reprogramming** (Krebs cycle, Lipid metabolism)\\n4.  **Lysosomal Program** (MiT family)\\n5.  **Distal Nephron Biology** (Mitochondria-rich)\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Deep Dive: Clear Cell RCC","config":{"nodeId":"Clear Cell RCC","entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Clear Cell Papillary","Translocation RCC"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## [[Clear Cell RCC]] (CCRCC)\\n\\n**Identity:** VHL/HIF-driven carcinoma; classic vascular pattern.\\n\\n### Diagnostic Triad\\n1) **Morphology**\\n- Clear cytoplasm + delicate capillary network\\n- Audit: necrosis, venous invasion, sarcomatoid/rhabdoid\\n\\n2) **IHC**\\n- [[PAX8]]+ confirms renal lineage\\n- [[CA9]]+ **diffuse “box”** (membranous all-around)\\n- [[CD10]]+, [[Vimentin]]+\\n\\n3) **Molecular**\\n- [[VHL Mutation]] / 3p loss pathway\\n\\n---\\n\\n### High-stakes discriminator (do not skip)\\n- **CA9 Box = CCRCC**\\n- **CA9 Cup + CK7 diffuse = stop → consider [[Clear Cell Papillary]]**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Prognostic lens (what changes the future)\\n- Stage dominates.\\n- WHO/ISUP grade changes risk assignment; grade 4 features are high risk.\\n- Necrosis + sarcomatoid/rhabdoid + venous invasion escalate risk materially.\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Calling [[Clear Cell Papillary]] as CCRCC → overtreatment.\\n- Missing sarcomatoid/rhabdoid/venous invasion → underestimation of relapse risk.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Critical Differential: The “Clear” Mimics","config":{"nodeId":"Clear Cell Papillary","entityRefs":["Clear Cell Papillary","Clear Cell RCC","Translocation RCC"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Clear Cell Papillary Renal Cell Tumor: indolent mimic of clear cell RCC\\n\\n### Diagnostic consequence\\nThis is an **overtreatment risk**. The pathologist’s job is to prevent harm from mislabeling.\\n\\n### Morphology\\n- Bland clear cells, often tubulopapillary\\n- Subnuclear vacuoles (“piano key” nuclei)\\n\\n### IHC flip (signature)\\n- [[CK7]] **diffuse strong**\\n- [[CA9]] **cup-like (basolateral)**\\n\\n### Contrast with CCRCC\\n- [[Clear Cell RCC]]: CK7 usually negative/patchy + CA9 **box**\\n- CCPRCT: CK7 diffuse + CA9 **cup**\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Unnecessary aggressive surveillance, anxiety, and potentially more extensive treatment decision-making.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Case Challenge: The \\"Clear\\" Trap","config":{"nodeId":"Clear Cell Papillary","entityRefs":["Clear Cell Papillary","Clear Cell RCC"],"showPrognosisPanel":false,"showPitfallPanel":false},"content":"\\n## Case Challenge: The Incidental Finding\\n\\n**Scenario:** 42F with a 2.0 cm renal mass found during gallbladder workup.\\n**Microscopy:** Nests of clear cells. The resident calls it \\"Clear Cell RCC, Grade 1\\".\\n\\n**The Twist:** You order markers. [[CA9]] shows a **\\"cup-like\\"** pattern (basolateral). [[CK7]] is **diffuse positive**.\\n\\n**The Pivot:** Does this profile fit the resident's diagnosis?\\n\\n**Resolution:** No. This is **[[Clear Cell Papillary]]** Renal Cell Tumor.\\n\\n**Diagnostic consequence:** This tumor is indolent. Assigning a \\"Grade\\" implies malignancy potential that doesn't exist. You saved the patient from \\"Cancer\\" anxiety and surveillance.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Deep Dive: The Pink Tumors","config":{"nodeId":"Chromophobe RCC","entityRefs":["Chromophobe RCC","Oncocytoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## [[Chromophobe RCC]] vs [[Oncocytoma]] (Eosinophilic renal mass)\\n\\n### [[Chromophobe RCC]]\\n- **Morphology:** plant-like borders, perinuclear halos, raisinoid nuclei\\n- **IHC:** [[CK7]] **diffuse**, [[CD117]]+\\n- **Reporting:** Not typically WHO/ISUP graded; stage + adverse features carry prognostic weight\\n\\n### [[Oncocytoma]]\\n- **Morphology:** uniform round nuclei, nests in loose stroma, often central scar\\n- **IHC:** [[CK7]] negative or scattered; [[CD117]]+\\n\\n---\\n\\n### The discriminator that saves you\\n- **CK7 diffuse → chromophobe**\\n- **CK7 scattered/negative → oncocytoma**\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Oncocytoma mislabeled malignant → overtreatment + anxiety.\\n- Chromophobe mislabeled benign → under-treatment/staging underappreciation.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Case Challenge: The \\"Pink\\" Trap","config":{"nodeId":"Chromophobe RCC","entityRefs":["Chromophobe RCC","Oncocytoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":false,"showPitfallPanel":false},"content":"\\n## Case Challenge: The Mahogany Tumor\\n\\n**Scenario:** 55M with a 6cm brown solid mass.\\n**Microscopy:** Sheets of eosinophilic cells. No perinuclear halos visible.\\n\\n**The Twist:** You suspect [[Oncocytoma]]. You order [[CK7]]. It comes back **diffuse strong positive**.\\n\\n**The Pivot:** Can Oncocytoma be diffuse CK7+?\\n\\n**Resolution:** Rarely. This pattern strongly favors **[[Chromophobe RCC]]** (Eosinophilic variant).\\n\\n**Diagnostic consequence:** Oncocytoma is benign and chromophobe RCC is malignant; diffuse CK7 in this setting changes the diagnosis, staging language, and follow-up plan.\\n        "},{"type":"summary","title":"Prognosis: WHO/ISUP Grading","config":{"entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Papillary RCC"],"showPrognosisPanel":true},"content":"\\n## WHO/ISUP Grading (CCRCC + Papillary RCC)\\n\\nWe grade based on **nucleolar prominence** (not Fuhrman).\\n\\n- **Grade 1:** nucleoli inconspicuous at 400×\\n- **Grade 2:** visible at 400×, not at 100×\\n- **Grade 3:** visible at 100×\\n- **Grade 4:** extreme pleomorphism OR **sarcomatoid/rhabdoid differentiation**\\n\\n### Expert rule\\n**Grade 4 is feature-based.** You cannot “average it away.”\\n        "},{"type":"summary","title":"Lecture Complete","config":{"entityRefs":["Clear Cell RCC","Clear Cell Papillary","Chromophobe RCC","Oncocytoma","Papillary RCC","Translocation RCC","Collecting Duct Carcinoma","Renal Medullary Carcinoma"]},"content":"\\n## Summary: Renal Mass Evaluation\\n\\n**Core flow**\\n- Start with morphology (Clear vs Pink vs Blue) **and** anatomic location.\\n- Use **PAX8** to confirm renal lineage.\\n- Use **CA9 pattern** (Box vs Cup) + **CK7 pattern** (Diffuse vs Scattered) to avoid the specific diagnostic errors.\\n- Integrate prognostic features early: **stage + grade + necrosis + sarcomatoid/rhabdoid + venous invasion**.\\n\\n**Red-alert zone**\\n- Medullary-based high-grade tumors (CDC/RMC) demand urgency and clinical correlation.\\n        "}],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["GU Pathology"],"provenance":{"entityCardsCount":8,"slideCount":12,"entityCards":[{"entityId":"Clear Cell RCC","summary":"VHL/HIF-driven renal carcinoma with classic clear cells + delicate vasculature; prognosis dominated by stage, grade, necrosis, and sarcomatoid/rhabdoid change.","keyMorphology":["Nests/alveoli/sheets of optically clear cells (lipid/glycogen)","Delicate ‘chicken-wire’ capillary network","Look-for: tumor necrosis; venous invasion; sarcomatoid/rhabdoid foci; infiltrative edges"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8","CA9","CD10","Vimentin"],"negative":["CK7 (usually negative or patchy)"],"patterns":["CA9 diffuse membranous ‘box’ pattern"]},"keyMolecular":["3p loss; VHL alteration (core pathway)"],"criticalDifferential":["Clear Cell Papillary","Translocation RCC","Papillary RCC"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CA9 ‘box’ vs ‘cup’ saves patients.** Box → favors CCRCC; Cup (basolateral) → favors Clear Cell Papillary."},{"type":"workflow","text":"If **young age**, papillary architecture, psammoma bodies, or atypical IHC pattern → **add MiT family (TFE3/TFEB) workup** and consider confirmatory testing."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Always comment on **necrosis**, **sarcomatoid/rhabdoid differentiation**, and **vascular invasion**, because these materially shift risk."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Avoid reflexively calling every clear tumor ‘CCRCC’—misclassifying an indolent mimic can drive overtreatment."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Pathologic stage (pT/pN)","effect":"unfavorable","notes":"Strongest overall driver of outcome."},{"name":"WHO/ISUP grade","effect":"unfavorable","notes":"Grade 4 features are high-risk regardless of ‘average’ grade."},{"name":"Tumor necrosis","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Sarcomatoid/rhabdoid differentiation","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Venous invasion","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Risk ranges from indolent (low stage/grade) to highly aggressive (advanced stage or grade 4 features).","Accurate subtyping prevents both under- and overtreatment."]},"managementImplications":["Overcalling indolent mimics → unnecessary aggressive surveillance/surgery decisions.","Missing sarcomatoid/rhabdoid/venous invasion → underestimation of relapse risk."]},{"entityId":"Clear Cell Papillary","summary":"Indolent clear cell renal tumor with CK7-diffuse and CA9 ‘cup’ pattern; key harm is overtreatment if miscalled as CCRCC.","keyMorphology":["Bland clear cells; often tubulopapillary architecture","Subnuclear vacuolization (‘piano-key’ nuclear alignment)","Typically lacks destructive invasion/necrosis in classic cases"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8","CK7"],"patterns":["CA9 ‘cup’ (basolateral) pattern","CK7 diffuse strong"]},"keyMolecular":["Not VHL/3p-driven in classic pattern (avoid assuming CCRCC biology)."],"criticalDifferential":["Clear Cell RCC","Papillary RCC","Translocation RCC"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CK7 diffuse + CA9 cup** is the signature pattern."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Calling this CCRCC is a classic source of **overtreatment and over-surveillance**."},{"type":"workflow","text":"If CA9 looks diffuse ‘boxy’ or morphology is atypical → re-cut, re-review, and widen the panel."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Benign/Indolent","drivers":[{"name":"Correct classification","effect":"contextual","notes":"Main risk is diagnostic error, not biology."}],"counseling":["Behavior is typically indolent; correct naming reduces unnecessary anxiety and follow-up intensity."]},"managementImplications":["Primary harm is overtreatment if misclassified as CCRCC."]},{"entityId":"Chromophobe RCC","summary":"Eosinophilic/pale renal carcinoma with plant-like borders and perinuclear halos; generally favorable but worsens with advanced stage or sarcomatoid change.","keyMorphology":["Plant-like cell borders; perinuclear halos","Raisinoid nuclei; pale to eosinophilic cytoplasm","Solid/trabecular growth; evaluate necrosis and sarcomatoid change"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["CK7 (diffuse)","CD117"],"patterns":["CK7 diffuse strong favors chromophobe over oncocytoma"]},"keyMolecular":["Multiple chromosomal losses (conceptual)"],"criticalDifferential":["Oncocytoma","Clear Cell RCC"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CK7 diffuse** is a major splitter from oncocytoma (CK7 negative/scattered)."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Chromophobe RCC is generally **not WHO/ISUP graded**; emphasize stage + adverse features."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Eosinophilic chromophobe can mimic oncocytoma—avoid single-marker diagnosis."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Generally Favorable","drivers":[{"name":"Pathologic stage","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Sarcomatoid transformation","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Tumor necrosis","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Often better prognosis than CCRCC at comparable stage, but adverse histology and stage escalation meaningfully worsen risk."]},"managementImplications":["Correct separation from oncocytoma prevents unnecessary ‘malignancy’ labeling, while correct malignant diagnosis ensures appropriate staging follow-up."]},{"entityId":"Oncocytoma","summary":"Benign renal oncocytic neoplasm; core goal is avoiding overcall as chromophobe RCC or other eosinophilic malignancy.","keyMorphology":["Nested/solid oncocytic cells with abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm","Round nuclei; degenerative atypia can occur (don’t over-interpret)","Often central scar grossly (not required)"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["CD117 (often)"],"negative":["CK7 (negative or scattered)"],"patterns":["CK7 scattered single cells (classic)"]},"criticalDifferential":["Chromophobe RCC"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CK7 scattered** + classic morphology supports oncocytoma; **CK7 diffuse** pushes chromophobe."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Degenerative atypia can look alarming; interpret it with architecture and the CK7 pattern."},{"type":"workflow","text":"If hybrid features exist, document uncertainty and integrate with imaging/gross (multifocality, bilateral disease, syndromic context)."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Benign/Indolent","drivers":[{"name":"Diagnostic accuracy","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["Classic oncocytoma behaves benignly; the dominant ‘risk’ is misclassification."]},"managementImplications":["Avoiding an erroneous malignant label reduces overtreatment and intensive surveillance."]},{"entityId":"Papillary RCC","summary":"Papillary renal carcinoma spectrum; prognosis varies—avoid confusing papillary architecture in CCRCC or MiT tumors as true papillary RCC.","keyMorphology":["Papillae with fibrovascular cores; often foamy macrophages","May show psammoma bodies (not exclusive)","Evaluate grade, necrosis, and invasive pattern"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8","CK7 (often)","AMACR (often)"],"patterns":["CA9 usually not diffuse ‘box’ (if it is, reconsider CCRCC)"]},"keyMolecular":["Commonly associated with chromosomal gains (conceptual); MET alterations in subsets."],"criticalDifferential":["Clear Cell RCC","Translocation RCC","Clear Cell Papillary"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"If papillary architecture + clear cells + odd IHC → broaden differential (CCRCC papillary areas, MiT RCC)."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Report **grade (WHO/ISUP applies)** and adverse features; quantify necrosis if present."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Stage","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"WHO/ISUP grade","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Necrosis","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Outcomes vary widely; correct entity assignment prevents inappropriate risk assumptions."]},"managementImplications":["Correct subtyping and grading informs surveillance intensity and systemic risk framing."]},{"entityId":"Translocation RCC","summary":"MiT family RCC (TFE3/TFEB) often mimics clear cell and papillary tumors; behavior variable—classification impacts risk and eligibility for targeted approaches/trials.","keyMorphology":["Clear and/or eosinophilic cells; often papillary architecture","Psammoma bodies may be present","May show high-grade cytology in discordance with architecture"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8"],"patterns":["TFE3/TFEB supportive but requires correlation/confirmation"]},"keyMolecular":["TFE3 or TFEB rearrangements (confirmatory testing often required)."],"criticalDifferential":["Clear Cell RCC","Papillary RCC","Clear Cell Papillary"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"When suspicion is high, **confirm with appropriate molecular methods** rather than relying on morphology alone."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Do not ‘force’ into CCRCC or papillary RCC when clinical age/pattern is discordant."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Subtype (TFE3 vs TFEB) + stage","effect":"contextual"},{"name":"Grade/cytologic aggressiveness","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Some behave indolently; others aggressive—correct labeling changes how clinicians frame risk."]},"managementImplications":["Correct classification avoids false reassurance or unnecessary escalation; supports appropriate additional testing."]},{"entityId":"Collecting Duct Carcinoma","summary":"High-grade medullary-based carcinoma with desmoplasia and infiltrative growth; typically aggressive with poor prognosis.","keyMorphology":["Infiltrative duct-like/tubulopapillary carcinoma","Prominent desmoplastic stroma","High-grade cytology; necrosis common"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8 (often)"],"patterns":["Broad high-grade carcinoma immunoprofile; integrate with location + morphology"]},"criticalDifferential":["Renal Medullary Carcinoma","Urothelial Carcinoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Anchor diagnosis to **medullary location + infiltrative desmoplasia + high-grade cytology**; exclude urothelial carcinoma when pelvis involvement is suspected."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Emphasize aggressive biology; document extent and invasion."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Highly Aggressive","drivers":[{"name":"Advanced stage at presentation","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Usually aggressive with high metastatic potential; classification is a red-alert communication."]},"managementImplications":["Correct identification drives urgent staging/oncology involvement and avoids under-treatment."]},{"entityId":"Renal Medullary Carcinoma","summary":"Sickle cell trait–associated, highly aggressive medullary carcinoma; diagnosis is a clinical-pathologic emergency signal.","keyMorphology":["Medullary-centered infiltrative high-grade carcinoma","Rhabdoid/sarcomatoid-like areas can occur","Necrosis and hemorrhage may be prominent"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["PAX8 (often)"],"patterns":["Integrate with clinical context (sickle trait)"]},"criticalDifferential":["Collecting Duct Carcinoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**Clinical correlation is mandatory:** ask/confirm **sickle cell trait/disease** context when suspected."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Use urgent, explicit language about aggressiveness and recommend prompt clinical correlation and staging workup."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Highly Aggressive","drivers":[{"name":"Intrinsic tumor biology + stage","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Extremely aggressive course; correct naming changes urgency and patient counseling."]},"managementImplications":["Avoids mislabeling as generic RCC and prevents dangerous underestimation of risk."]}]}},{"id":"testicular_mass_eval","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/lectures/lectures.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Testicular Mass Evaluation","category":"GU Pathology","summary":"Master the diagnostic workup of testicular neoplasms, from Germ Cell Tumors to Sex Cord-Stromal entities.","body":"## Testicular Mass Evaluation: Full Transcript\\n\\n**Introduction**\\nWelcome to the evaluation of Testicular Masses. The vast majority of tumors you will encounter here are Germ Cell Tumors (GCTs). Your diagnostic workup must always be driven by clinical data: the patient's age is the single most powerful discriminator. Ideally, you will also have serum markers—AFP, beta-hCG, and LDH—which serve as both diagnostic clues and monitoring tools.\\nBiologically, the key concept to frame your thinking is the \\"postpubertal malignant pathway,\\" defined by the presence of isochromosome 12p. This pathway drives the common malignancies like Seminoma, Embryonal Carcinoma, and postpubertal Teratoma.\\n\\n**Anatomic Context**\\nUnderstanding the anatomy is straightforward but vital for staging. Tumors arise from the tubules (GCTs, Sertoli tumors) or the interstitium (Leydig tumors, Lymphoma). Documenting invasion into the rete testis, tunica albuginea, or spermatic cord is critical, as these are the checkpoints that escalate the pT stage.\\n\\n**Diagnostic Algorithm**\\nOur diagnostic logic proceeds in steps.\\nStep 1: Age. In a prepubertal child, a teratoma is often benign. In a postpubertal male, it is assumed malignant. In a man over 60, your first thought should be Lymphoma.\\nStep 2: Lineage. Is it a Germ Cell Tumor (SALL4+, OCT4+) or a Sex Cord-Stromal Tumor (Inhibin+, Calretinin+)?\\nStep 3: Subtyping GCTs. This is the high-stakes work. You must distinguish Seminoma (CD117 positive, CD30 negative) from Embryonal Carcinoma (CD30 positive, CD117 negative).\\nStep 4: Mixed Tumors. Pure tumors are less common than you think. Sample heterogeneous areas and quantify each identified component, especially teratoma, because residual teratoma is chemotherapy-resistant and usually requires surgical management.\\n\\n**Deep Dive: Seminoma and Precursors**\\nClassical Seminoma is the most common pure GCT. Histologically, look for sheets of uniform cells with clear cytoplasm, distinct borders, and fibrous septa containing lymphocytes. The immunoprofile is distinct: OCT4+, SALL4+, and CD117+, but crucially CD30 negative.\\nIts precursor, Germ Cell Neoplasia In Situ (GCNIS), shares this profile and is found in the adjacent tubules. Identifying GCNIS supports a postpubertal germ cell tumor diagnosis and should prompt evaluation for adjacent invasive components and contralateral risk context.\\nSeminomas generally have an excellent prognosis, but the diagnostic risk is missing a small component of non-seminomatous tumor (NSGCT), which would require a more aggressive treatment regimen.\\n\\n**Deep Dive: Non-Seminomatous GCTs (NSGCT)**\\nThese are the aggressive players.\\nEmbryonal Carcinoma is high-grade, \\"ugly,\\" and necrotic. It stains with CD30.\\nYolk Sac Tumor shows reticular or microcystic patterns and is positive for AFP and Glypican-3.\\nChoriocarcinoma consists of biphasic trophoblasts, is often hemorrhagic, and is marked by high hCG.\\nTeratoma, in the postpubertal setting, is malignant. It can contain cartilage, glands, or neural tissue. Its chemo-resistance makes accurate quantification essential for surgical planning.\\n\\n**Special Scenarios**\\nBeware the \\"bilateral lymphoma-risk scenario.\\" If you see a bilateral testicular mass in an elderly man (over 60), do not default to Seminoma. Stain for CD45. This is often Testicular Lymphoma, a systemic disease treated with chemotherapy, not orchiectomy alone.\\nAnother pitfall is the \\"Serologic Mismatch.\\" If your slides show only Seminoma, but the patient's serum AFP is elevated, you have missed a Yolk Sac or Embryonal component (or it is in the block you didn't print). You cannot call it pure Seminoma; it must be managed as a Mixed Germ Cell Tumor.\\n\\n**Summary**\\nIn summary: Age changes the differential diagnosis and expected tumor biology in testicular pathology. Never let a single marker override morphology. Use CD117 vs CD30 to split the main GCT types. Quantify all components in mixed tumors. And always keep a high index of suspicion for lymphoma in older patients. Accurate diagnosis here directly dictates whether a patient gets surveillance, radiation, chemotherapy, or surgery.","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[{"type":"intro","title":"Introduction to Testicular Pathology","config":{"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Evaluation of the Testicular Mass\\n\\nMost testicular tumors are **Germ Cell Tumors (GCTs)**.\\n\\n### High-yield clinical data\\n- **Age:** the most powerful first discriminator.\\n- **Serum markers:** AFP, β-hCG, LDH.\\n- **Ultrasound:** solid intratesticular mass = malignant until proven otherwise.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### The prognostic superstructure (hidden skeleton)\\n- **Postpubertal malignant GCTs** are defined by **i(12p)/12p amplification**.\\n- **Seminoma** generally has excellent prognosis and radiosensitivity.\\n- **NSGCT components** (embryonal, yolk sac, choriocarcinoma, teratoma) change biology and management.\\n- **Teratoma** is clinically critical: **chemo-resistant**; postpubertal context = malignant potential.\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Missing NSGCT components can lead to undertreatment.\\n- Calling lymphoma as GCT in older men can misroute care entirely.\\n        "},{"type":"anatomy","title":"Anatomic Context","config":{"system":"gu"},"content":"\\n## Testicular Anatomy\\n\\n- **Tubules:** origin of most GCTs and Sertoli tumors.\\n- **Interstitium:** Leydig tumors and lymphoma.\\n- **Rete testis / Tunica albuginea:** staging relevance; breach changes T-stage.\\n\\n**Sampling logic**\\n- If mixed tumor suspected: sample broadly; heterogeneity is the rule.\\n        "},{"type":"algorithm","title":"Diagnostic Algorithm","config":{"algorithmId":"algo_testis","entityRefs":["Seminoma","GCNIS","Embryonal Carcinoma","Yolk Sac Tumor","Choriocarcinoma","Teratoma","Mixed Germ Cell Tumor","Testicular Lymphoma","Spermatocytic Tumor","Leydig Cell Tumor","Sertoli Cell Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## The Diagnostic Chain of Thought (diagnosis + prognosis together)\\n\\n### Step 1: Age Context (prognosis encoded)\\n- **Prepubertal:** pure yolk sac tumor or teratoma patterns have different implications.\\n- **Postpubertal:** malignant GCT pathway (think i(12p)).\\n- **Elderly (>60):** rule out **[[Testicular Lymphoma]]** early; also consider **[[Spermatocytic Tumor]]**.\\n\\n### Step 2: Germ cell vs sex cord–stromal\\n- **GCT:** [[SALL4]]+, [[OCT4]]+ (context-dependent)\\n- **Sex cord:** [[Inhibin]]+, [[Calretinin]]+\\n\\n### Step 3: Seminoma vs NSGCT splitter (high-stakes)\\n- **Seminoma:** [[CD117]]+ / [[CD30]]-\\n- **Embryonal:** [[CD30]]+ / [[CD117]]-\\n\\n### Step 4: Mixed tumors (default assumption)\\n- Quantify **every component**; highlight teratoma (chemo-resistant).\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Galaxy of Testicular Tumors","config":{"nodeId":"Seminoma","highlightGroup":"Testis","entityRefs":["Seminoma","Embryonal Carcinoma","Yolk Sac Tumor","Teratoma","Testicular Lymphoma","Spermatocytic Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Visualizing Relationships\\n\\n**Key hubs**\\n- **[[i(12p)]] / 12p amplification:** postpubertal malignant GCT backbone.\\n- **[[SALL4]] & [[OCT4]]:** pan-germ cell logic (interpret with context).\\n- **[[Inhibin]]:** sex cord–stromal bridge.\\n- **[[CD45]]:** lymphoma branch.\\n\\n**Expert note**\\nEntities cluster by shared markers, but diagnosis requires **architecture + cytology + context**—not marker-only thinking.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Deep Dive: Seminoma","config":{"nodeId":"Seminoma","entityRefs":["Seminoma","Embryonal Carcinoma","Mixed Germ Cell Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Classic Seminoma\\n\\n### Histology\\n- Sheets of uniform large cells with clear cytoplasm\\n- Distinct borders, prominent nucleoli\\n- Fibrous septa with lymphocytes\\n\\n### IHC\\n- **Positive:** [[OCT4]], [[SALL4]], [[CD117]], [[PLAP]], [[D2-40]]\\n- **Negative:** [[CD30]] (key), cytokeratin usually negative or focal dot-like\\n\\n### Prognostic meaning\\n- Typically excellent prognosis and treatment responsiveness.\\n- **High-stakes pitfall:** missing a NSGCT component → undertreatment.\\n\\n**Single discriminator that saves you**\\n- **CD117 vs CD30** split, plus aggressive morphology sampling.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"The Precursor: GCNIS","config":{"nodeId":"GCNIS","entityRefs":["GCNIS","Seminoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Germ Cell Neoplasia In Situ (GCNIS)\\n\\n### Appearance\\n- Atypical germ cells within tubules, along basement membrane\\n- Often absent spermatogenesis in affected tubules\\n\\n### IHC\\n- Mirrors seminoma: [[OCT4]]+, [[CD117]]+, [[PLAP]]+\\n\\n### Diagnostic consequence (prognostic context)\\n- Confirms a postpubertal germ cell tumor background and prompts evaluation for adjacent invasive components and contralateral risk context.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Case Challenge: The Serologic Mismatch","config":{"nodeId":"Seminoma","entityRefs":["Seminoma","Yolk Sac Tumor","Embryonal Carcinoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":false,"showPitfallPanel":false},"content":"\\n## Case Challenge: The Serologic Mismatch\\n\\n**Scenario:** 28M, testicular mass. Serum **AFP is 800 ng/mL**.\\n**Microscopy:** You see 10 slides of classic **[[Seminoma]]** (lymphocytes, fried-egg cells).\\n\\n**The Cognitive Conflict:** Can pure Seminoma make AFP?\\n\\n**The Pivot:** Never. Pure Seminoma is AFP negative.\\n\\n**Resolution:** There is a missed **[[Yolk Sac Tumor]]** or **[[Embryonal Carcinoma]]** component hiding in the block you didn't submit, or it represents \\"burned out\\" tumor.\\n\\n**Action:** Submit more tissue. If negative, report as \\"Mixed Germ Cell Tumor\\" based on serology.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Deep Dive: Non-Seminomatous GCTs","config":{"nodeId":"Embryonal Carcinoma","entityRefs":["Embryonal Carcinoma","Yolk Sac Tumor","Choriocarcinoma","Teratoma","Mixed Germ Cell Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Non-Seminomatous GCTs (NSGCT)\\n\\n### 1) [[Embryonal Carcinoma]]\\n- “Ugly” high-grade stem-cell phenotype\\n- Necrosis + high mitoses\\n- **IHC:** [[CD30]]+, [[OCT4]]+, [[CD117]]-\\n\\n### 2) [[Yolk Sac Tumor]]\\n- Reticular/microcystic patterns; Schiller–Duval bodies\\n- **IHC:** [[AFP]]+, [[Glypican-3]]+, [[SALL4]]+\\n- Serum AFP often elevated (diagnostic + monitoring)\\n\\n### 3) [[Choriocarcinoma]]\\n- Biphasic trophoblasts; hemorrhagic/necrotic\\n- **IHC:** [[hCG]]+; serum hCG often very high\\n- High propensity for early hematogenous spread\\n\\n### 4) [[Teratoma]]\\n- Chemo-resistant; postpubertal context = malignant potential\\n- Must be quantified in mixed tumors\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Mislabeling as seminoma can misroute therapy.\\n- Missing teratoma can mislead expectations of chemo response.\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Reality Check: Mixed Tumors","config":{"nodeId":"Teratoma","entityRefs":["Mixed Germ Cell Tumor","Teratoma","Embryonal Carcinoma","Seminoma","Yolk Sac Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Mixed Germ Cell Tumors (the default reality)\\n\\n### Diagnostic consequence\\nReport each component percentage because teratoma can require surgery, embryonal carcinoma and choriocarcinoma increase clinical risk, and yolk sac tumor explains AFP elevation.\\n\\n### Component logic\\n- Teratoma: chemo-resistant → surgical relevance\\n- Embryonal/choriocarcinoma: aggressive biology\\n- Seminoma: treatment-sensitive component\\n\\n### Reporting rule\\n- Estimate % of each component (don’t round away the small but critical ones).\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Deep Dive: Sex Cord-Stromal Tumors","config":{"nodeId":"Leydig Cell Tumor","entityRefs":["Leydig Cell Tumor","Sertoli Cell Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Sex Cord–Stromal Tumors\\n\\n### [[Leydig Cell Tumor]]\\n- Endocrine active (androgen/estrogen), may cause gynecomastia\\n- **Reinke crystals** supportive (not required)\\n- **IHC:** [[Inhibin]]+, [[Calretinin]]+, [[Melan-A]]+\\n- Prognosis usually favorable; **risk is feature-based** (size, necrosis, vascular invasion, mitoses, atypia)\\n\\n### [[Sertoli Cell Tumor]]\\n- Tubule formation\\n- Syndromic associations can exist\\n- **IHC:** [[Inhibin]]+, [[Calretinin]]+\\n- Prognosis usually favorable; adverse features modify risk\\n        "},{"type":"network","title":"Case Challenge: The Elderly Patient","config":{"nodeId":"Testicular Lymphoma","entityRefs":["Testicular Lymphoma","Seminoma"],"showPrognosisPanel":false,"showPitfallPanel":false},"content":"\\n## Case Challenge: The \\"Bilateral\\" Trap\\n\\n**Scenario:** 78-year-old male presents with bilateral testicular enlargement.\\n**Microscopy:** Diffuse sheets of atypical cells crushing tubules.\\n\\n**The Instinct:** \\"It looks like Seminoma.\\"\\n\\n**The Pivot:** Look at the age. Primary GCT in a 78-year-old is exceedingly rare. Bilaterality is a red flag.\\n\\n**Test:** **[[CD45]]**.\\n\\n**Resolution:** Positive. This is **[[Testicular Lymphoma]]**.\\n\\n**Diagnostic consequence:** Positive CD45 redirects the diagnosis to lymphoma staging and systemic therapy; orchiectomy alone is not adequate treatment.\\n        "},{"type":"summary","title":"Lecture Complete","config":{"entityRefs":["Seminoma","GCNIS","Embryonal Carcinoma","Yolk Sac Tumor","Choriocarcinoma","Teratoma","Mixed Germ Cell Tumor","Testicular Lymphoma","Spermatocytic Tumor","Leydig Cell Tumor","Sertoli Cell Tumor"],"showPrognosisPanel":true,"showPitfallPanel":true},"content":"\\n## Summary: Testicular Mass\\n\\n**Core takeaways**\\n1) **Age changes the differential** (prepubertal vs postpubertal vs >60).\\n2) **Markers must match morphology** (don’t let one stain decide the case).\\n3) **CD117 vs CD30** is a high-yield split (seminoma vs embryonal).\\n4) **Mixed tumors are common**: quantify components; highlight teratoma chemo resistance.\\n5) **Older men**: rule out lymphoma early (CD45 gate).\\n\\n**Reporting consequence**\\n- Undertreating mixed/NSGCT.\\n- Misrouting lymphoma into GCT pathway.\\n- Overcalling indolent entities into aggressive frameworks.\\n        "}],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["GU Pathology"],"provenance":{"entityCardsCount":11,"slideCount":12,"entityCards":[{"entityId":"Seminoma","summary":"Most common pure GCT with excellent prognosis; key harm is missing a non-seminomatous component and undertreating.","keyMorphology":["Sheets/nests of large uniform cells with clear cytoplasm (‘fried egg’)","Fibrous septa with lymphocytes","Granulomas may be present (pitfall)"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["OCT4","SALL4","CD117","PLAP","D2-40"],"negative":["CD30 (typically)","Cytokeratin (usually negative or focal dot-like)"]},"keyMolecular":["i(12p)/12p amplification in postpubertal malignant pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Embryonal Carcinoma","Spermatocytic Tumor"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CD117+ / CD30−** is the classic split from embryonal carcinoma."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Do not call ‘pure seminoma’ if any area looks ‘ugly’—sample heavily and hunt for mixed components."},{"type":"reporting","text":"If mixed tumor: **quantify components**; this affects risk and therapy planning."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Generally Favorable","drivers":[{"name":"Stage","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Presence of NSGCT components","effect":"unfavorable","notes":"Mixed histology alters management."}],"counseling":["Often curable; accurate classification prevents undertreatment of mixed/NSGCT tumors."]},"managementImplications":["Misclassifying mixed tumor as seminoma can change chemo/surgery decisions."]},{"entityId":"GCNIS","summary":"In-situ precursor for most postpubertal GCTs; indicates field effect and contralateral risk context.","keyMorphology":["Atypical germ cells along basement membrane within seminiferous tubules","Often decreased/absent spermatogenesis in involved tubules"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["OCT4","CD117","PLAP"]},"keyMolecular":["Associated with postpubertal malignant GCT pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Seminoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Documenting GCNIS supports postpubertal pathway and informs contralateral surveillance considerations."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Contextual","drivers":[{"name":"Presence indicates malignant pathway","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["Not a metastatic lesion itself, but prognostically meaningful as a precursor and risk marker."]},"managementImplications":["Improves clinical understanding of pathway and future risk framing."]},{"entityId":"Embryonal Carcinoma","summary":"Aggressive NSGCT component; high-grade cytology and necrosis; missing it is a common high-stakes error.","keyMorphology":["Solid/glandular/papillary growth with crowded pleomorphic nuclei","Frequent mitoses and necrosis (‘ugly’)","Infiltrative destructive pattern"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["CD30","OCT4","Cytokeratin (often)"],"negative":["CD117 (typically)"]},"keyMolecular":["i(12p)/12p amplification in postpubertal pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Seminoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**CD30+ / CD117−** is the inverse of seminoma."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Quantify component percentage in mixed tumors—this can influence risk and response expectations."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Aggressive","drivers":[{"name":"Stage","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Tumor burden in mixed GCT","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["More aggressive than seminoma; correct identification prevents undertreatment."]},"managementImplications":["Missing embryonal component can misroute therapy strategy."]},{"entityId":"Yolk Sac Tumor","summary":"AFP/Glypican-3 positive NSGCT component; prepubertal vs postpubertal context strongly modifies meaning and risk.","keyMorphology":["Reticular/microcystic (‘lace-like’) pattern","Schiller–Duval bodies (when present)","Hyaline globules"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["AFP","Glypican-3","SALL4"]},"keyMolecular":["Postpubertal component usually within i(12p) malignant pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Embryonal Carcinoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Always integrate **serum AFP** and age context; AFP is both diagnostic and monitoring marker."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Prepubertal vs postpubertal context","effect":"contextual"},{"name":"Stage","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Biology and implications differ by developmental context; correct framing prevents incorrect risk assumptions."]},"managementImplications":["Accurate component identification supports correct marker interpretation and follow-up logic."]},{"entityId":"Choriocarcinoma","summary":"Highly aggressive trophoblastic GCT component with hemorrhage and very high hCG; small primaries can have massive metastases.","keyMorphology":["Biphasic: cytotrophoblasts + syncytiotrophoblasts","Marked hemorrhage and necrosis (‘blood bath’)"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["hCG"]},"keyMolecular":["i(12p)/12p amplification in postpubertal pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Embryonal Carcinoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"reporting","text":"Explicitly communicate aggressive biology; correlate with serum hCG."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Highly Aggressive","drivers":[{"name":"Early hematogenous spread propensity","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Often aggressive with early metastasis; prompt staging and systemic therapy planning context."]},"managementImplications":["Avoids underestimation when tumor is small but biologically high-risk."]},{"entityId":"Teratoma","summary":"Chemo-resistant component; postpubertal teratoma is malignant by context (metastatic potential) regardless of ‘mature’ appearance.","keyMorphology":["Somatic tissues from ≥1 germ layer (cartilage, glands, neural, squamous, etc.)","‘Fruitcake’ heterogeneity"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["(Variable by tissue type)"]},"keyMolecular":["Postpubertal malignant pathway association; behavior driven by context"],"criticalDifferential":["Mixed Germ Cell Tumor"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"**Postpubertal teratoma ≠ benign** (context-dependent malignancy)."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Quantify % teratoma in mixed GCT; highlight chemo resistance explicitly."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Postpubertal context","effect":"unfavorable","notes":"Metastatic potential exists."},{"name":"Resectability / residual disease","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["Clinically important because it can persist after chemotherapy and require surgical management."]},"managementImplications":["Ensures clinicians don’t assume chemo will eradicate teratomatous disease."]},{"entityId":"Mixed Germ Cell Tumor","summary":"Rule, not exception; prognosis and therapy are driven by component percentages—reporting is prognostication.","keyMorphology":["Composite of seminoma + one or more NSGCT elements","Component-specific patterns coexist in different regions"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["Component-dependent; use targeted panels per region"]},"keyMolecular":["Usually i(12p)/12p amplification in postpubertal pathway"],"criticalDifferential":["Seminoma","Embryonal Carcinoma","Teratoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Sample generously; if any region looks different, stain it separately."},{"type":"reporting","text":"Report **each component and %** (especially teratoma) because therapy response differs."},{"type":"pitfall","text":"Avoid single-block ‘one-marker’ diagnosis; mixed tumors punish shortcuts."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Intermediate/Variable","drivers":[{"name":"Stage","effect":"unfavorable"},{"name":"Component biology (teratoma, choriocarcinoma, embryonal)","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Risk varies; percentages meaningfully influence expected response and relapse risk framing."]},"managementImplications":["Directly impacts chemo expectations and surgical planning."]},{"entityId":"Testicular Lymphoma","summary":"Most common testicular malignancy in older men; systemic disease implications—do not miss in >60.","keyMorphology":["Diffuse interstitial infiltrate between tubules","Often spares tubules early; may be bilateral"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["CD45"]},"criticalDifferential":["Seminoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"discriminator","text":"In men **>60**, rule out lymphoma early—CD45 gate is high yield."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Aggressive","drivers":[{"name":"Systemic disease behavior","effect":"unfavorable"}],"counseling":["Behavior reflects systemic lymphoma patterns; correct diagnosis changes staging and therapy entirely."]},"managementImplications":["Prevents misrouting into GCT management pathways."]},{"entityId":"Spermatocytic Tumor","summary":"Indolent tumor of older men; lacks i(12p) and lacks GCNIS; avoid confusing with seminoma.","keyMorphology":["Distinct cytology compared to seminoma (often mixed cell populations in classic teaching)","Typically lacks prominent lymphoid septa"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["(Variable; use exclusion + context)"]},"keyMolecular":["Lacks i(12p); not derived from GCNIS"],"criticalDifferential":["Seminoma"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Use **age + absence of GCNIS** logic to avoid overcalling seminoma."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Generally Favorable","drivers":[{"name":"Correct classification","effect":"favorable"}],"counseling":["Typically indolent; correct naming avoids overtreatment."]},"managementImplications":["Avoids unnecessary aggressive therapy aligned to malignant GCT pathways."]},{"entityId":"Leydig Cell Tumor","summary":"Sex cord–stromal tumor with endocrine effects; mostly benign, but adverse features should be communicated for risk framing.","keyMorphology":["Sheets/nests of polygonal cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm","Reinke crystals (supportive; not required)","Assess necrosis, vascular invasion, high mitotic activity, marked atypia"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["Inhibin","Calretinin","Melan-A"]},"criticalDifferential":["Sertoli Cell Tumor"],"pearls":[{"type":"reporting","text":"Comment on adverse features (size, necrosis, vascular invasion, mitotic rate, atypia) to guide malignancy risk discussions."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Generally Favorable","drivers":[{"name":"Adverse histologic features","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["Most behave benignly; a minority behave aggressively—risk is feature-driven."]},"managementImplications":["Improves counseling and follow-up intensity decisions."]},{"entityId":"Sertoli Cell Tumor","summary":"Sex cord tumor with tubule formation; syndromic associations exist; prognosis usually favorable but feature-dependent.","keyMorphology":["Tubules/cords of Sertoli-like cells","Evaluate for atypia, necrosis, invasion, mitotic rate"],"keyIHC":{"positive":["Inhibin","Calretinin"]},"criticalDifferential":["Leydig Cell Tumor"],"pearls":[{"type":"workflow","text":"Consider syndromic context (e.g., Peutz–Jeghers, Carney complex) when clinically suggested."}],"prognosis":{"tier":"Generally Favorable","drivers":[{"name":"Adverse features and stage","effect":"contextual"}],"counseling":["Typically favorable; correct classification supports appropriate genetic/clinical correlation when relevant."]},"managementImplications":["Ensures right downstream clinical correlation without over-escalating."]}]}}]`),t=[{id:`bladder_path_core_principles`,sourceRepo:`didactic_series`,sourcePath:`src/content/lectures/customLectures.ts`,contentType:`lecture`,title:`Bladder Pathology: Core Principles`,category:`Genitourinary Pathology`,summary:`Boards-first lecture for tomorrow: bladder biopsy/TURBT orientation, papillary grading, CIS, invasion, variants, and high-yield mimics.`,body:`## Bladder Pathology: Core Principles

**Opening frame**
This lecture is built around the specimen that changes management fastest in bladder pathology: the TURBT. Your job is not just to say "urothelial carcinoma." Your job is to answer the questions that determine whether the patient stays in the non-muscle-invasive pathway or crosses into a cystectomy-level disease state.

### Learning objectives
- Separate **papillary**, **flat**, and **invasive** bladder lesions before chasing subtype details.
- Grade papillary urothelial neoplasms using architectural order versus disorder.
- Distinguish **reactive atypia**, **dysplasia**, and **carcinoma in situ** in flat lesions.
- Recognize why **muscularis propria invasion** is the single most important line in the report.
- Identify aggressive variants and common inflammatory or metaplastic mimics that create diagnostic errors.

## Why bladder is high yield
- **Painless gross hematuria** is the classic presentation until proven otherwise.
- The biggest modifiable risk factor is **smoking**.
- Other major associations include **aromatic amines**, **cyclophosphamide**, **radiation**, and for pure squamous carcinoma in endemic settings, **Schistosoma haematobium**.
- Bladder tumors show a **field effect**: synchronous or metachronous lesions may appear anywhere along the urothelial tract.

## Specimen-first mindset
Before you grade anything, orient the specimen:
1. Is this a **biopsy/TURBT** or a **cystectomy**?
2. Is **muscularis propria** actually present?
3. Is the lesion **papillary**, **flat**, or clearly **invasive**?
4. Are there treatment effects such as **BCG change**, radiation atypia, or cautery artifact?

If muscularis propria is absent in a high-grade or invasive-appearing TURBT, you must say so. That is not a minor footnote. It directly affects whether the clinician can stage the tumor confidently.

## The three major buckets
### 1. Papillary lesions
Think in a ladder:
- **Urothelial papilloma**: benign exophytic lesion with essentially normal urothelium.
- **PUNLMP**: thicker urothelium with minimal architectural complexity and no meaningful cytologic atypia.
- **Low-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma**: orderly but neoplastic, mild atypia, polarity mostly maintained.
- **High-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma**: architectural disorder, pleomorphism, loss of polarity, brisk mitoses, often necrosis.

### 2. Flat lesions
The key differential is:
- **Reactive atypia**
- **Urothelial dysplasia**
- **Urothelial carcinoma in situ**

### 3. Invasive lesions
The most important question is depth:
- **pT1**: invades lamina propria
- **pT2**: invades muscularis propria

That distinction is the management hinge.

## Papillary grading: features that determine classification
When you grade papillary urothelial neoplasia, ignore the urge to over-focus on isolated ugly nuclei. Grade is about the integrated pattern:
- How orderly is the epithelium?
- Is polarity preserved?
- Are umbrella cells retained?
- Are papillae simple or fused/complex?
- Are mitoses rare and basal, or frequent and disorderly?

### Low grade
- Mild nuclear enlargement
- Relative polarity retained
- Papillae still recognizable and organized
- Recurs often but progresses less often than high grade

### High grade
- Marked pleomorphism and hyperchromasia
- Frequent mitoses at multiple epithelial levels
- Architectural disarray
- High risk of recurrence, invasion, and progression

## Flat urothelial lesions: high-risk diagnostic errors
### Reactive atypia
- Uniform nuclei
- Prominent nucleoli can be present
- Clinical inflammation or instrumentation often explains the picture
- Umbrella cell maturation is preserved

### CIS
- Full-thickness atypia
- Marked pleomorphism
- Discohesion and denudation may be present
- Often clinically occult but biologically dangerous

### Helpful adjuncts in the right context
- **CK20**: umbrella-cell restricted in reactive settings; full-thickness in CIS
- **p53**: wild-type/reactive patterns versus strong diffuse or null-type aberrancy
- **CD44**: retained basally in reactive lesions, often lost in CIS

These stains support morphology. They do not rescue a poorly conceptualized H&E read.

## Invasion and staging: the management hinge
For invasive urothelial carcinoma, the report must communicate where the tumor is:
- **Lamina propria only (pT1)** still carries substantial risk, especially if high grade.
- **Muscularis propria invasion (pT2)** defines muscle-invasive disease and changes therapy dramatically.

### TURBT pitfalls
- Tangentially cut muscle bundles can mislead.
- Muscularis mucosae is not muscularis propria.
- Desmoplasia, single cells, and retraction can support invasion, but interpretation must stay anatomically disciplined.
- If no muscularis propria is present, say so explicitly.

## Variant histology you cannot afford to miss
### Micropapillary
- Small tight nests in lacunar spaces
- Aggressive behavior
- Often managed more aggressively than conventional morphology would suggest

### Plasmacytoid
- Discohesive infiltrative cells
- High risk of advanced spread

### Nested
- Bland-appearing nests that can be deceptively low-key cytologically
- Architecture and depth save you from undercalling it

### Sarcomatoid
- Spindled or pleomorphic high-grade morphology
- Signals aggressive biology

### Squamous and adenocarcinomatous differentiation
- Pure **squamous carcinoma** raises specific etiologic considerations
- **Adenocarcinoma**, especially urachal/enteric-type, requires correlation with location and lineage context

## Common mimics and non-neoplastic lesions
### Cystitis spectrum
- Acute bacterial cystitis: neutrophil-rich inflammation
- Chronic/follicular cystitis: lymphoplasmacytic infiltrates and follicles
- Interstitial cystitis: chronic pain syndrome with negative cultures
- Hemorrhagic cystitis: drug, radiation, or viral injury
- Malakoplakia: Michaelis-Gutmann bodies in immunocompromised settings

### Metaplastic/reactive lesions
- **Cystitis glandularis**
- **Nephrogenic adenoma**
- **BCG effects**
- Radiation atypia

These are where overcalling carcinoma happens if you detach histology from context.

## Lineage and ancillary studies
When you need to confirm urothelial differentiation or exclude a mimic:
- **GATA3**
- **p63**
- **Uroplakin**

For flat lesions, return to the triad:
- **CK20**
- **p53**
- **CD44**

For enteric-type lesions or urachal tumors, broader panels may be necessary, but do not let immunostains replace anatomic reasoning.

## Tomorrow's sign-out script
If you have to teach this tomorrow, teach the bladder in this order:
1. Hematuria and specimen type
2. Papillary versus flat versus invasive
3. Low-grade versus high-grade papillary disease
4. Reactive atypia versus CIS
5. Lamina propria versus muscularis propria invasion
6. High-yield aggressive variants
7. Non-neoplastic mimics and treatment effects

If learners leave with that diagnostic sequence, they can safely approach the majority of bladder cases.

## Final take-home points
- **Bladder pathology is a specimen-orientation discipline before it is a buzzword discipline.**
- **Papillary grade and depth of invasion drive prognosis.**
- **CIS is flat, high grade, and easy to miss if you are casual.**
- **Muscularis propria status must be explicit in TURBT reporting.**
- **Micropapillary, plasmacytoid, nested, and sarcomatoid variants are board-relevant and clinically consequential.**
- **Reactive and inflammatory mimics are common; context plus disciplined morphology prevents harm.**`,learningObjectives:[`Distinguish papillary, flat, and invasive bladder lesions.`,`Grade papillary urothelial neoplasms using WHO/ISUP-style morphologic logic.`,`Separate reactive atypia, dysplasia, and CIS in flat lesions.`,`Recognize why muscularis propria invasion is the decisive staging threshold in bladder pathology.`],slides:[{type:`intro`,title:`Bladder TURBT Reporting Consequences`,content:`Hematuria, smoking exposure, and field effect set risk context; the TURBT report determines grade, invasion status, muscularis propria adequacy, and next management step.`},{type:`framework`,title:`Specimen-First Approach`,content:`Biopsy/TURBT versus cystectomy, presence of muscularis propria, and artifact awareness.`},{type:`algorithm`,title:`Three Buckets`,content:`Papillary lesions, flat lesions, and invasive lesions.`},{type:`grading`,title:`Papillary Ladder`,content:`Papilloma, PUNLMP, low-grade papillary UC, high-grade papillary UC.`},{type:`pitfall`,title:`Flat Lesions`,content:`Reactive atypia versus dysplasia versus CIS; where CK20, p53, and CD44 help.`},{type:`staging`,title:`Invasion and Staging`,content:`Lamina propria versus muscularis propria invasion and TURBT pitfalls.`},{type:`variant`,title:`Aggressive Variants`,content:`Micropapillary, plasmacytoid, nested, sarcomatoid, squamous, and adenocarcinoma patterns.`},{type:`mimic`,title:`Inflammatory and Metaplastic Mimics`,content:`Cystitis patterns, malakoplakia, BCG effects, radiation change, and nephrogenic adenoma.`},{type:`ihc`,title:`Ancillary Studies`,content:`GATA3, p63, uroplakin for lineage; CK20, p53, CD44 for flat lesions.`},{type:`workflow`,title:`Tomorrow’s Sign-Out Script`,content:`Teach bladder in order: specimen, architecture, grade, CIS, invasion, variants, mimics.`},{type:`summary`,title:`High-Yield Takeaways`,content:`Grade plus depth plus variant histology are the decisive bladder teaching points.`}],mcqs:[{topic:`Bladder Pathology`,question:`Which pathologic finding in a TURBT most decisively shifts a bladder tumor into the muscle-invasive category?`,choices:[`Diffuse CK20 staining`,`Lamina propria invasion`,`Muscularis propria invasion`,`Presence of necrosis`],answer:`Muscularis propria invasion`,rationale:`Invasion into muscularis propria defines pT2 disease and is the key management threshold for muscle-invasive bladder cancer.`},{topic:`Bladder Pathology`,question:`A flat bladder lesion shows full-thickness atypia with diffuse CK20 and loss of basal CD44. What is the best diagnosis?`,choices:[`Reactive atypia`,`Urothelial dysplasia`,`Carcinoma in situ`,`Nephrogenic adenoma`],answer:`Carcinoma in situ`,rationale:`Full-thickness atypia with supportive CK20/CD44 staining is classic for urothelial carcinoma in situ.`},{topic:`Bladder Pathology`,question:`Which bladder variant is classically associated with tight nests in lacunar spaces and aggressive behavior?`,choices:[`Nested variant`,`Micropapillary variant`,`Squamous differentiation`,`PUNLMP`],answer:`Micropapillary variant`,rationale:`Micropapillary urothelial carcinoma is a high-yield aggressive variant with characteristic lacunar nesting.`}],flashcards:[{front:`What is the single most important staging threshold in a TURBT?`,back:`Whether tumor invades muscularis propria (pT2).`,tag:`staging`},{front:`Classic presentation of bladder cancer?`,back:`Painless gross hematuria.`,tag:`clinical`},{front:`What stain pattern supports CIS over reactive atypia?`,back:`CK20 full-thickness with aberrant p53 and loss of basal CD44.`,tag:`ihc`},{front:`High-yield aggressive bladder variants?`,back:`Micropapillary, plasmacytoid, nested, and sarcomatoid.`,tag:`variants`}],references:[`Robbins & Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease, 10th ed.`,`WHO Classification of Tumours of the Urinary System and Male Genital Organs.`,`The Cancer Genome Atlas Research Network. Comprehensive molecular characterization of urothelial bladder carcinoma. Nature. 2014;507:315-322.`],tags:[`bladder`,`urothelial carcinoma`,`genitourinary pathology`,`TURBT`,`CIS`],provenance:{authoringMode:`custom-local-lecture`,assembledFrom:[`src/content/tutorials/tutorials.normalized.json`,`src/content/downloads_imports/normalized/tutorials.normalized.json`,`src/content/derived/stainbrain_printable/algorithms.from_service.json`,`src/content/syllabus/syllabus.normalized.json`],readiness:`ready-to-deliver`}}],n=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"penile_who_complete_pathology","sourceRepo":"didactic_series","sourcePath":"src/content/lectures/gu_who_complete_lectures.normalized.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Penile Pathology: WHO-Complete Sign-Out Lecture","category":"Genitourinary Pathology","summary":"Resident-facing penile pathology lecture covering WHO 2022 penile precursor lesions and tumors with biopsy, penectomy, HPV, invasion, margin, and mimic logic.","body":"## Penile Pathology: WHO-Complete Sign-Out Lecture\\n\\n### Opening frame\\nPenile pathology is not a memorization exercise in squamous carcinoma names. The real sign-out task is to decide whether the lesion is a precursor, invasive squamous carcinoma, non-squamous primary tumor, or secondary tumor; then to report the features that change treatment: HPV association, depth and anatomic compartment of invasion, grade, lymphovascular invasion, perineural invasion, urethral/corporal involvement, and margins.\\n\\n### Learning objectives\\n- Separate HPV-associated, HPV-independent, and NOS penile squamous lesions using morphology first and p16 support when appropriate.\\n- Diagnose penile precursor lesions without overcalling invasion on small biopsies.\\n- Recognize the major invasive SCC patterns and know which patterns are now grouped under broader WHO 2022 categories.\\n- Build a penectomy report around depth, corpus spongiosum/cavernosum, urethra, LVI, PNI, and margins.\\n- Stop the SCC algorithm when melanoma, Paget disease, mesenchymal/hematolymphoid disease, or metastasis is more plausible.\\n\\n## Specimen-first workflow\\n1. Identify specimen type: shave/punch biopsy, wide local excision, partial penectomy, total penectomy, or lymph node specimen.\\n2. Identify anatomic site: glans, foreskin, coronal sulcus, shaft skin, urethral mucosa, corpus spongiosum, corpus cavernosum.\\n3. Decide whether the lesion is intraepithelial, superficially invasive, deeply invasive, or non-squamous.\\n4. For invasive carcinoma, report subtype/pathogenesis, grade, depth, involved structures, LVI, PNI, and all relevant margins.\\n\\n## Precursor lesions\\n### Low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion / condyloma / PeIN 1\\nThis is the low-grade HPV-associated bucket: LSIL, condyloma acuminatum, and PeIN1. The sign-out error is overcalling condyloma as warty carcinoma. Look for true destructive invasion at the base before escalating.\\n\\n### High-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion / PeIN 2-3\\nThis includes HSIL, usual PeIN, basaloid PeIN, warty PeIN, PeIN2, and PeIN3. The pattern is high-grade squamous atypia without stromal invasion. Block-type p16 supports HPV-associated disease, but invasion is still an H&E/anatomic diagnosis.\\n\\n### Differentiated penile intraepithelial neoplasia\\nDifferentiated PeIN, or dPeIN, is the HPV-independent precursor. It can look deceptively mature. The diagnostic clue is basal atypia with abnormal premature maturation, often in a background of chronic inflammatory dermatosis. It is the precursor you miss if you only look for full-thickness basaloid atypia.\\n\\n## Invasive SCC: pathogenesis first\\n### HPV-associated squamous cell carcinoma, NOS\\nUse this when the carcinoma is HPV-associated but does not fit a dominant named pattern. Block-type p16 is practical support, but morphology and clinical context still matter.\\n\\n### Basaloid squamous cell carcinoma\\nBasaloid SCC, including papillary-basaloid morphology, is an HPV-associated high-risk pattern. It shows nests or sheets of basaloid cells, often with comedonecrosis or abrupt keratinization. Exclude lymphoma, melanoma, and small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma when the biopsy is crushed or very blue.\\n\\n### Warty squamous cell carcinoma\\nWarty SCC is the condyloma mimic that has destructive invasion. Sample the base. A beautiful papillary surface does not make the lesion benign.\\n\\n### Warty-basaloid squamous cell carcinoma\\nWarty-basaloid SCC contains both warty and basaloid HPV-associated morphology. In a penectomy specimen, report the dominant patterns and relative percentages when meaningful.\\n\\n### Clear cell squamous cell carcinoma\\nClear cell SCC is rare and can trigger a metastatic clear cell RCC differential. Confirm squamous lineage and avoid losing the penile SCC staging workflow.\\n\\n### Lymphoepithelioma-like squamous cell carcinoma\\nThis tumor has poorly differentiated epithelial cells in a dense inflammatory background. The pitfall is lymphoma. Confirm epithelial lineage before calling it inflammatory or hematolymphoid.\\n\\n## Invasive SCC: HPV-independent and NOS categories\\n### HPV-independent squamous cell carcinoma, NOS\\nThis is a useful honest category when the carcinoma is HPV-independent in morphology or p16 pattern but lacks a more specific pattern. If HPV status cannot be determined, use squamous cell carcinoma, NOS rather than forcing the tumor into a pathogenesis bucket.\\n\\n### Usual-type squamous cell carcinoma\\nUsual-type SCC is the common keratinizing HPV-independent pattern. WHO 2022 groups pseudohyperplastic SCC, pseudoglandular SCC, and acantholytic SCC within the usual-type spectrum. The reporting job is depth, grade, structures, LVI, PNI, and margins.\\n\\n### Verrucous squamous cell carcinoma\\nVerrucous SCC includes carcinoma cuniculatum as a related pattern. It is well differentiated and pushing or burrowing. The practical diagnostic error is missing a conventional usual-type invasive SCC component. If present, report mixed squamous cell carcinoma and estimate components.\\n\\n### Papillary squamous cell carcinoma, NOS\\nPapillary SCC, NOS is exophytic and HPV-independent. Separate it from warty SCC and verrucous carcinoma by morphology, p16 pattern, and base architecture.\\n\\n### Sarcomatoid squamous cell carcinoma\\nSarcomatoid SCC is aggressive and can mimic sarcoma or melanoma. Keratins and p40 may be focal. Do not under-sample the transition to conventional carcinoma.\\n\\n### Adenosquamous and mucoepidermoid carcinoma\\nThis rare entity has squamous plus glandular or mucinous differentiation. Exclude urethral adenocarcinoma and metastasis before final sign-out.\\n\\n### Mixed squamous cell carcinoma\\nMixed SCC means two or more clinically meaningful SCC patterns. The practical rule is to report percentages when feasible, especially when a low-grade-looking verrucous/cuniculatum component is admixed with usual invasive SCC.\\n\\n### Squamous cell carcinoma, NOS\\nSCC NOS is appropriate when HPV association or subtype cannot be determined confidently. It is not a failure; it is safer than false precision on a superficial, crushed, or cauterized biopsy.\\n\\n## Non-squamous and secondary tumors\\n### Extramammary Paget disease\\nPaget disease presents as an intraepithelial glandular-appearing lesion and may be primary or secondary. Use CK7, GATA3, urothelial markers, and GI markers according to the differential, then search for invasive or underlying carcinoma.\\n\\n### Melanoma\\nPenile melanoma can be pigmented or amelanotic. Use SOX10, S100, Melan-A, and HMB45 to confirm lineage. Once melanoma is favored, switch to melanoma reporting parameters rather than SCC staging habits.\\n\\n### Mesenchymal, hematolymphoid, and metastatic tumors of the penis\\nAny non-squamous morphology should stop the SCC algorithm. Consider sarcoma, lymphoma, and metastasis. The biopsy triage issue is real: lymphoma may need flow cytometry, and sarcoma/metastasis may need molecular or broad lineage workup.\\n\\n## Penectomy reporting script\\n- Tumor site and size.\\n- Histologic type and HPV association when determinable.\\n- Grade.\\n- Depth of invasion and involved structures: lamina propria, corpus spongiosum, corpus cavernosum, urethra, skin/soft tissue.\\n- LVI and PNI.\\n- Margins: urethral, corporal, soft tissue/skin, deep margin as applicable.\\n- Associated precursor lesion.\\n- In mixed tumors, report component percentages when feasible.\\n\\n## Final take-home points\\n- Penile SCC classification starts with HPV-associated versus HPV-independent versus NOS, but the patient outcome is driven by invasion, structures, LVI/PNI, nodes, and margins.\\n- dPeIN is subtle and easy to miss; HSIL is easier to see but still needs an invasion search.\\n- Verrucous/cuniculatum lesions require base sampling to exclude mixed usual-type invasive SCC.\\n- Sarcomatoid SCC, melanoma, lymphoma, Paget disease, and metastasis are the cases where reflexively staying in the SCC lane causes harm.","learningObjectives":["Classify penile squamous precursor lesions into LSIL/condyloma/PeIN1, HSIL/PeIN2-3, and differentiated PeIN.","Separate HPV-associated, HPV-independent, and NOS penile SCC categories using morphology and p16 support.","Report penectomy specimens using depth, anatomic compartment, LVI, PNI, and margin logic.","Recognize non-squamous penile tumors and secondary tumors that require a different diagnostic workflow."],"slides":[{"type":"intro","title":"Why Penile Pathology Is a Sign-Out Problem","content":"Biopsy and penectomy decisions revolve around precursor vs invasive disease, HPV pathway, anatomic invasion, and margins.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/52/Squamous_carcinoma_of_the_penis_--_low_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Squamous_carcinoma_of_the_penis_--_low_mag.jpg","alt":"Low-power micrograph of penile squamous cell carcinoma","caption":"This low-power penile SCC image shows invasive architecture; the report must state depth of invasion, involved anatomic structures, LVI/PNI, and margin status.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"framework","title":"Specimen First","content":"Orient glans, foreskin, shaft skin, urethra, corpus spongiosum, corpus cavernosum, and margins before subtyping.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c2/Penile_verrucous_carcinoma.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Penile_verrucous_carcinoma.jpg","alt":"Gross photograph of penile verrucous carcinoma","caption":"This exophytic penile mass requires sampling of the base; superficial biopsy cannot exclude destructive invasion or a mixed usual-type SCC component.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"ihc","title":"HPV Pathway","content":"p16 block positivity supports HPV-associated SCC; non-block p16 supports HPV-independent disease only in the right morphology.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/24/Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_--_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_--_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of penile intraepithelial neoplasia","caption":"Penile intraepithelial neoplasia provides the visual bridge into HPV-associated precursor disease.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"grading","title":"Precursor Lesions","content":"LSIL/condyloma/PeIN1, HSIL/PeIN2-3, and differentiated PeIN.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fb/Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_--_intermed_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_--_intermed_mag.jpg","alt":"Intermediate-power micrograph of penile intraepithelial neoplasia","caption":"Intermediate-power PeIN helps learners compare intraepithelial atypia with invasive carcinoma.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"variant","title":"HPV-Associated SCC","content":"Basaloid, warty, warty-basaloid, clear cell, lymphoepithelioma-like, and HPV-associated SCC NOS.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0b/Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_-_alt_--_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Penile_intraepithelial_neoplasia_-_alt_--_high_mag.jpg","alt":"Alternative high-power micrograph of penile intraepithelial neoplasia","caption":"This PeIN image shows basaloid/warty HPV-associated atypia; use block-pattern p16 as support and search the biopsy base for invasion.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"variant","title":"HPV-Independent SCC","content":"Usual-type, verrucous/cuniculatum, papillary NOS, sarcomatoid, adenosquamous/mucoepidermoid, mixed, and HPV-independent SCC NOS.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2d/Squamous_carcinoma_of_the_penis_--_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Squamous_carcinoma_of_the_penis_--_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of penile squamous cell carcinoma","caption":"This keratinizing penile SCC image shows an HPV-independent usual-type pattern; report depth, grade, LVI/PNI, involved structures, and margins.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"mimic","title":"Non-Squamous Stops","content":"Paget disease, melanoma, mesenchymal/hematolymphoid tumors, and metastases stop the SCC algorithm.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2e/Extramammary_Paget_disease_-_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Extramammary_Paget_disease_-_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of extramammary Paget disease","caption":"This extramammary Paget disease image shows intraepidermal glandular cells; stop the SCC algorithm and evaluate primary versus secondary Paget disease with CK7, GATA3, urothelial, and GI markers as indicated.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"workflow","title":"Penectomy Report","content":"Type/pathway, grade, depth, structures, LVI, PNI, margins, precursor lesion, and component percentages.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7d/Micrograph_of_penile_verrucous_carcinoma_-_20x_and_200x.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Micrograph_of_penile_verrucous_carcinoma_-_20x_and_200x.jpg","alt":"Composite micrograph of penile verrucous carcinoma at low and high power","caption":"Paired low- and high-power verrucous carcinoma image highlights base assessment and reporting consequences.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"summary","title":"Resident Takeaways","content":"HPV pathway organizes the diagnosis; anatomy and margins drive management.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8d/Micrograph_of_penile_verrucous_carcinoma_-_200x.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Micrograph_of_penile_verrucous_carcinoma_-_200x.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of penile verrucous carcinoma","caption":"This verrucous carcinoma image shows bland squamous proliferation with a pushing profile; sign-out still requires base assessment, invasion status, and margin status.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}}],"mcqs":[{"topic":"Penile Pathology","question":"Which finding most practically supports HPV-associated penile SCC in daily sign-out?","choices":["Patchy p16 staining","Block-type p16 staining","Diffuse CK7 staining","Loss of INI1"],"answer":"Block-type p16 staining","rationale":"Block-type p16 immunohistochemistry is the practical supportive test for HPV-associated penile SCC when interpreted with morphology."},{"topic":"Penile Pathology","question":"A well-differentiated burrowing penile SCC with labyrinthine channels is best grouped with which WHO 2022 pattern?","choices":["Basaloid SCC","Verrucous SCC / carcinoma cuniculatum pattern","Clear cell SCC","Lymphoepithelioma-like SCC"],"answer":"Verrucous SCC / carcinoma cuniculatum pattern","rationale":"Carcinoma cuniculatum is now handled as a pattern within the verrucous carcinoma spectrum."}],"flashcards":[{"front":"Most important practical test for HPV-associated penile SCC?","back":"Block-type p16 staining, interpreted with morphology.","tag":"penis"},{"front":"HPV-independent precursor of penile SCC?","back":"Differentiated penile intraepithelial neoplasia (dPeIN).","tag":"penis"},{"front":"What must be sampled in verrucous/cuniculatum penile lesions?","back":"The base and any heterogeneous areas to exclude mixed usual-type invasive SCC.","tag":"penis"}],"references":["WHO Classification of Tumours: Urinary and Male Genital Tumours, 5th ed., Volume 8. IARC; 2022.","Moch H, Amin MB, Berney DM, et al. The 2022 WHO Classification of Tumours of the Urinary System and Male Genital Organs-Part A. Eur Urol. 2022.","Menon S, Moch H, Berney DM, et al. WHO 2022 classification of penile and scrotal cancers: updates and evolution. Histopathology. 2023."],"tags":["penis","penile carcinoma","PeIN","HPV","WHO 2022","genitourinary pathology"],"provenance":{"authoringMode":"who-coverage-batch","manifest":"src/content/gu/who_gu_entity_manifest.json","readiness":"resident-review-draft","requiresExpertReview":true}},{"id":"testicular_who_complete_pathology","sourceRepo":"didactic_series","sourcePath":"src/content/lectures/gu_who_complete_lectures.normalized.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Testicular and Paratesticular Pathology","category":"Genitourinary Pathology","summary":"Pathology residency lecture covering WHO 2022 testicular and paratesticular tumors, including GCNIS-associated germ cell tumors, germ cell tumors unrelated to GCNIS, sex cord-stromal tumors, rete/epididymal/paratesticular tumors, lymphoma, and metastases.","body":"## Testicular and Paratesticular Pathology\\n\\n### Opening frame\\nTestis pathology is age, pathway, and component accounting. Before naming a tumor, decide whether the patient is prepubertal, postpubertal, or older; whether the tumor arises in a GCNIS background or is unrelated to GCNIS; whether serum markers fit the slides; and whether the specimen is a routine orchiectomy, post-chemotherapy residual mass, paratesticular mass, epididymal mass, or lymphoma/metastasis workup.\\n\\n### Learning objectives\\n- Use age and serum markers as first-line diagnostic data rather than afterthoughts.\\n- Separate germ cell tumors arising in a GCNIS background from tumors unrelated to GCNIS.\\n- Quantify mixed GCT components and identify treatment-changing components such as teratoma, embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, choriocarcinoma, and somatic-type malignancy.\\n- Recognize sex cord-stromal tumors and assess malignant risk features using mitotic activity per mm2 rather than informal HPF language.\\n- Work up paratesticular, epididymal, rete testis, mesothelial, lymphoma, and metastatic tumors without forcing them into the germ cell pathway.\\n\\n## Specimen-first workflow\\n1. Start with age: prepubertal, postpubertal, or older adult.\\n2. Pull serum AFP, beta-hCG, and LDH before finalizing.\\n3. Inspect background testis for GCNIS and impaired spermatogenesis.\\n4. Sample heterogeneous gross areas and the spermatic cord margin.\\n5. Report tumor size, histologic type, component percentages, rete testis/tunica/epididymis/spermatic cord involvement, LVI, margins, and relevant treatment effect.\\n\\n## Non-invasive lesions arising in a GCNIS background\\n### Germ cell neoplasia in situ\\nGCNIS is the background lesion of most postpubertal malignant GCTs. Look for atypical germ cells along the basement membrane with impaired spermatogenesis. OCT4, SALL4, PLAP, and CD117 can support the diagnosis.\\n\\n### Specific forms of intratubular germ cell neoplasia\\nSpecific forms include intratubular seminoma, intratubular embryonal carcinoma, and intratubular trophoblast. These usually support the invasive tumor pathway rather than replacing invasive component reporting.\\n\\n### Gonadoblastoma\\nGonadoblastoma occurs in dysgenetic gonads with Y-chromosome material and contains germ cells plus immature sex cord cells. It can mimic seminoma and has high invasive transformation risk.\\n\\n## Invasive germ cell tumors arising in a GCNIS background\\n### Seminoma\\nSeminoma is in the germinoma family. It shows uniform clear cells, crisp borders, fibrous septa, and lymphocytes. OCT4, SALL4, and CD117 are positive, while CD30 is negative. Seminoma with syncytiotrophoblastic cells can mildly elevate hCG but should not be treated as choriocarcinoma.\\n\\n### Embryonal carcinoma\\nEmbryonal carcinoma is a high-grade primitive epithelial NSGCT component. It is commonly necrotic and CD30/OCT4 positive. Quantify it in mixed tumors.\\n\\n### Yolk sac tumor, postpubertal type\\nPostpubertal yolk sac tumor is the AFP-linked NSGCT component. It has reticular, microcystic, glandular, papillary, solid, hepatoid, or Schiller-Duval patterns. If AFP is elevated, pure seminoma is unsafe until yolk sac tumor is excluded by sampling.\\n\\n### Choriocarcinoma\\nChoriocarcinoma is a hemorrhagic, aggressive trophoblastic tumor with cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast. Even a small component can matter clinically because of aggressive hematogenous spread and high hCG.\\n\\n### Other trophoblastic tumors\\nOther trophoblastic tumors include placental site trophoblastic tumor, epithelioid trophoblastic tumor, and cystic trophoblastic tumor patterns. They are rare but should be recognized in mixed GCT and hCG-discordant cases.\\n\\n### Teratoma, postpubertal type\\nPostpubertal teratoma is malignant by pathway even when mature. It is chemo-resistant, so quantify it in mixed tumors and in post-chemotherapy residual masses.\\n\\n### Teratoma with somatic-type malignancy\\nTeratoma with somatic-type malignancy includes embryonic neuroectodermal tumor, rhabdomyosarcoma arising in teratoma, nephroblastoma arising in teratoma, carcinoma, or other frank somatic malignancies. WHO 2022 replaces primitive neuroectodermal tumor language with embryonic neuroectodermal tumor terminology. Name the somatic malignancy because it can change therapy.\\n\\n### Mixed germ cell tumor\\nMixed GCT is the default reality in many postpubertal tumors. Report every component percentage. Teratoma, embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, and trophoblastic components change clinical expectations.\\n\\n## Germ cell tumors unrelated to GCNIS\\n### Spermatocytic tumor\\nSpermatocytic tumor usually occurs in older patients, is unrelated to GCNIS, and is often indolent. It should not be signed out as classic seminoma.\\n\\n### Spermatocytic tumor with sarcomatous differentiation\\nSarcomatous differentiation converts the clinical conversation. Sample high-grade fleshy or necrotic areas and characterize the sarcomatous component.\\n\\n### Yolk sac tumor, prepubertal type\\nPrepubertal yolk sac tumor is the classic malignant pediatric germ cell tumor and is not the same biologic pathway as postpubertal yolk sac tumor.\\n\\n### Teratoma, prepubertal type\\nPrepubertal teratoma, including dermoid cyst and epidermoid cyst patterns when appropriate, generally behaves benignly when truly unrelated to GCNIS. Do not apply postpubertal malignant-teratoma assumptions to the wrong pathway.\\n\\n### Prepubertal-type testicular neuroendocrine tumor\\nThe old carcinoid terminology is retired. Most examples fit a prepubertal-type teratoma-associated neuroendocrine tumor pathway. Exclude metastasis and document Ki-67/mitotic features when clinically relevant.\\n\\n## Sex cord-stromal tumors\\n### Leydig cell tumor\\nLeydig cell tumor is often yellow-brown and may be endocrine active. Inhibin, calretinin, and SF1 support lineage. Assess malignant Leydig cell tumor features: size, necrosis, atypia, vascular invasion, extra-testicular invasion, and mitotic activity per mm2.\\n\\n### Sertoli cell tumor\\nSertoli cell tumor includes conventional forms, large cell calcifying Sertoli cell tumor, intratubular hyalinizing Sertoli cell neoplasia, and Sertoliform cystadenoma now handled in the Sertoli category. Think syndromes: Carney complex and Peutz-Jeghers in the right morphology.\\n\\n### Granulosa cell tumor\\nGranulosa cell tumor includes adult and juvenile forms. Juvenile granulosa cell tumor is a pediatric differential for yolk sac tumor. Use sex cord markers and age-pathway logic.\\n\\n### Other sex cord-stromal tumors\\nOther sex cord-stromal tumors include mixed sex cord-stromal tumor, sex cord-stromal tumor NOS, signet ring stromal tumor, myoid gonadal stromal tumor, and thecoma/fibroma group tumors. WHO 2022 specifically defines signet ring stromal tumor and myoid gonadal stromal tumor. Do not confuse signet ring stromal tumor with metastatic GI signet ring carcinoma.\\n\\n## Rete, epididymal, ovarian-type, and paratesticular tumors\\n### Ovarian-type epithelial tumors\\nOvarian-type epithelial tumors include serous cystadenoma, mucinous cystadenoma, borderline serous tumor, and serous carcinoma patterns in the testis/paratestis region. Exclude metastasis and mesothelial tumors.\\n\\n### Tumors of the collecting ducts and rete testis\\nRete testis tumors include adenoma of rete testis and adenocarcinoma of rete testis. The diagnosis depends on accurate hilar/rete localization and exclusion of metastasis and mesothelioma.\\n\\n### Paratesticular mesothelial tumors\\nParatesticular mesothelial tumors include adenomatoid tumor, well-differentiated papillary mesothelial tumor, and malignant mesothelioma of the tunica vaginalis. WHO 2022 defines well-differentiated papillary mesothelial tumor as a favorable tumor when strictly noninvasive.\\n\\n### Tumors of the epididymis\\nEpididymal tumors include cystadenoma of epididymis, papillary cystadenoma, and rare epididymal adenocarcinoma. Bilateral papillary cystadenoma can suggest von Hippel-Lindau syndrome; metastatic RCC is a key mimic.\\n\\n## Hematolymphoid and metastatic tumors\\n### Hematolymphoid and metastatic tumors of the testis\\nIn an older man, bilateral testicular enlargement or diffuse destructive infiltrate is lymphoma until excluded. Use CD45 early. Metastases also occur and should be worked up by history and morphology rather than forced into the GCT algorithm.\\n\\n## Resident sign-out script\\n- Age and serum markers in the first internal sentence.\\n- Tumor arising in a GCNIS background versus tumor unrelated to GCNIS.\\n- Pure versus mixed tumor, with percentages.\\n- Teratoma and somatic-type malignancy explicitly named.\\n- Rete testis, tunica, epididymis, spermatic cord, LVI, and margin status.\\n- For sex cord-stromal tumors, malignant risk features and mitotic activity per mm2.\\n- In older patients, exclude lymphoma and metastasis before finalizing seminoma.\\n\\n## Final take-home points\\n- Age is diagnostic data; use it before ordering stains or naming the tumor.\\n- AFP mismatch overrides a clean-looking seminoma slide set until sampling proves otherwise.\\n- Postpubertal teratoma is not pediatric teratoma.\\n- Mixed GCT component percentages are treatment data.\\n- Paratesticular, epididymal, rete, mesothelial, lymphoma, and metastatic tumors should not be forced into the germ cell tumor algorithm.","learningObjectives":["Use age, serum markers, GCNIS, and morphology to classify testicular tumors by WHO 2022 pathway.","Quantify mixed germ cell tumor components and recognize post-chemotherapy treatment-changing residual disease.","Identify sex cord-stromal tumor categories and assess malignant risk features.","Recognize paratesticular, epididymal, rete, mesothelial, hematolymphoid, and metastatic tumors that require non-GCT workflows."],"slides":[{"type":"intro","title":"Age and Pathway Define the Differential","content":"Prepubertal tumors, postpubertal germ cell tumors, and tumors in older adults do not share one algorithm.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/Seminoma_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Seminoma_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of seminoma","caption":"This seminoma image shows uniform clear cells and lymphocyte-rich septa; correlate age, AFP, beta-hCG, LDH, and background GCNIS before finalizing a pure seminoma diagnosis.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"anatomy","title":"Specimen Orientation","content":"Orchiectomy sampling must capture background testis, rete/tunica/epididymis/spermatic cord, and heterogeneous tumor areas.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f0/Seminoma_with_syncytiotrophoblasts_-_low_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Seminoma_with_syncytiotrophoblasts_-_low_mag.jpg","alt":"Low-power micrograph of seminoma with syncytiotrophoblasts","caption":"This seminoma with syncytiotrophoblasts image can explain mild beta-hCG elevation; elevated AFP still requires additional sampling for yolk sac tumor or another NSGCT component.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"framework","title":"Tumors Arising in a GCNIS Background","content":"GCNIS, seminoma, embryonal carcinoma, postpubertal yolk sac tumor, choriocarcinoma, trophoblastic tumors, postpubertal teratoma, somatic-type malignancy, and mixed GCT.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f6/Mixed_germ_cell_tumour_-_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Mixed_germ_cell_tumour_-_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of mixed germ cell tumor","caption":"This mixed germ cell tumor image requires a report that lists each component and percentage; embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, choriocarcinoma, teratoma, and somatic-type malignancy change staging discussions, serum marker interpretation, chemotherapy response, or surgical planning.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"framework","title":"Tumors Unrelated to GCNIS","content":"Spermatocytic tumor, prepubertal yolk sac tumor, prepubertal teratoma, and prepubertal-type neuroendocrine tumor.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3a/Spermatocytic_seminoma_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Spermatocytic_seminoma_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of spermatocytic tumor","caption":"This spermatocytic tumor image should trigger a diagnosis in an older patient that is unrelated to GCNIS; do not diagnose classic seminoma unless morphology and OCT4/CD117/GCNIS findings support seminoma.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"variant","title":"Sex Cord-Stromal Tumors","content":"Leydig, Sertoli, granulosa, mixed/NOS, signet ring stromal, myoid gonadal stromal, and thecoma/fibroma group tumors.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b8/Sertoli_cell_tumour_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Sertoli_cell_tumour_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of Sertoli cell tumor","caption":"This Sertoli cell tumor image should trigger sex cord-stromal markers such as inhibin, calretinin, and SF1 rather than a germ cell tumor marker panel alone.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"variant","title":"Paratesticular and Adnexal Tumors","content":"Ovarian-type epithelial tumors, rete testis tumors, mesothelial tumors, and epididymal tumors.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7b/Adenomatoid_tumour_-_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Adenomatoid_tumour_-_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of adenomatoid tumor","caption":"This adenomatoid tumor image should be worked up as a benign paratesticular mesothelial tumor; confirm localization and avoid signing it out as an intratesticular germ cell tumor.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"mimic","title":"Lymphoma and Metastasis in Older Patients","content":"Lymphoma and metastasis must be excluded before defaulting to seminoma in older patients.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6e/DLBCL_of_testis_--_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:DLBCL_of_testis_--_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of the testis","caption":"This DLBCL image shows diffuse lymphoid replacement of testis; in older patients or bilateral masses, order CD45 early and do not finalize seminoma until lymphoma is excluded.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"workflow","title":"Mixed GCT Report","content":"List and quantify every component; teratoma and somatic-type malignancy are treatment-changing.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/91/Yolk_sac_tumour_--_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Yolk_sac_tumour_--_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of yolk sac tumor of the testis","caption":"This yolk sac tumor image explains AFP elevation; if AFP is elevated in an apparent seminoma, submit more tissue and report yolk sac tumor percentage when identified.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}},{"type":"summary","title":"Resident Takeaways","content":"Classify the tumor by GCNIS relationship, list every mixed GCT component with percentage, and state treatment-relevant features: teratoma, somatic-type malignancy, LVI, rete/tunica/epididymis/spermatic cord involvement, and margins.","visualAid":{"imageUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c5/Embryonal_carcinoma_-_high_mag.jpg","sourcePageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Embryonal_carcinoma_-_high_mag.jpg","alt":"High-power micrograph of embryonal carcinoma","caption":"This embryonal carcinoma image shows a high-grade CD30/OCT4-positive NSGCT component; quantify it in mixed tumors because it changes risk assessment and treatment planning.","credit":"Wikimedia Commons"}}],"mcqs":[{"topic":"Testicular Pathology","question":"A 29-year-old man has a testicular tumor with classic seminoma morphology but serum AFP is markedly elevated. What is the safest next step?","choices":["Sign out pure seminoma","Ignore AFP if CD117 is positive","Submit/search more tissue for yolk sac or other NSGCT component","Call spermatocytic tumor"],"answer":"Submit/search more tissue for yolk sac or other NSGCT component","rationale":"Pure seminoma should not elevate AFP; a serologic mismatch requires additional sampling and mixed-GCT thinking."},{"topic":"Testicular Pathology","question":"Which WHO 2022 terminology replaces the older 'carcinoid tumor' language for most testicular examples?","choices":["Embryonic neuroectodermal tumor","Prepubertal-type testicular neuroendocrine tumor","Spermatocytic tumor","Epithelioid trophoblastic tumor"],"answer":"Prepubertal-type testicular neuroendocrine tumor","rationale":"WHO 2022 retires carcinoid terminology and classifies most testicular examples as prepubertal-type testicular neuroendocrine tumor."}],"flashcards":[{"front":"Testicular mass in a man over 60?","back":"Exclude lymphoma early, especially if bilateral or diffuse.","tag":"testis"},{"front":"Postpubertal teratoma reporting point?","back":"Quantify it because it is chemo-resistant and can drive surgery.","tag":"testis"},{"front":"WHO 2022 testis update for PNET terminology?","back":"Use embryonic neuroectodermal tumor rather than primitive neuroectodermal tumor.","tag":"testis"}],"references":["WHO Classification of Tumours: Urinary and Male Genital Tumours, 5th ed., Volume 8. IARC; 2022.","Moch H, Amin MB, Berney DM, et al. The 2022 WHO Classification of Tumours of the Urinary System and Male Genital Organs-Part A. Eur Urol. 2022.","Berney DM, Cree I, Rao V, et al. An introduction to the WHO 5th edition 2022 classification of testicular tumours. Histopathology. 2022."],"tags":["testis","paratestis","germ cell tumor","sex cord-stromal tumor","WHO 2022","genitourinary pathology"],"provenance":{"authoringMode":"who-coverage-batch","manifest":"src/content/gu/who_gu_entity_manifest.json","readiness":"resident-review-draft","requiresExpertReview":true}}]`),r=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"ioc-overview-breast-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Breast Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Breast Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Evaluate lumpectomy margins and sentinel lymph nodes; distinguish invasive carcinoma from benign mimickers.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is the lesion malignant, what is the histologic type, and are the margins clear?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Evaluate lumpectomy margins and sentinel lymph nodes; distinguish invasive carcinoma from benign mimickers.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Complex sclerosing lesions and radial scars may mimic invasive carcinoma; correlation with permanent sections and immunostains may be necessary.\\n- Representative Specimens: Lumpectomy margins, core needle biopsies, sentinel lymph nodes.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Tubular\\n- Sclerosing\\n- Cribriform","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Breast Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Breast Surgery","triad":["Tubular","Sclerosing","Cribriform"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-endocrine-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Thyroid Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Endocrine Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Triage thyroid lesions into papillary, follicular‑patterned and other categories; recognize that follicular carcinoma cannot be diagnosed on frozen section.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is this thyroid nodule malignant and, if so, should a total thyroidectomy be performed?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Triage thyroid lesions into papillary, follicular‑patterned and other categories; recognize that follicular carcinoma cannot be diagnosed on frozen section.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Follicular carcinoma requires capsular and/or vascular invasion on permanent sections; never overcall invasion on frozen.\\n- Representative Specimens: Lobectomy, isthmusectomy, subtotal or completion thyroidectomy.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Papillary\\n- Follicular\\n- SolidSpindle","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Endocrine Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Endocrine Surgery","triad":["Papillary","Follicular","SolidSpindle"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-gynecologic-oncology","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Gynecologic Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Gynecologic Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Classify ovarian and endometrial tumors into major histologic categories; determine need for comprehensive staging or debulking.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is the adnexal or uterine mass benign, borderline, or malignant, and does it require staging?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Classify ovarian and endometrial tumors into major histologic categories; determine need for comprehensive staging or debulking.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Borderline serous tumors can be difficult to distinguish from invasive carcinoma on frozen; deferral may be prudent.\\n- Representative Specimens: Oophorectomy, salpingo‑oophorectomy, hysterectomy, omentectomy.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Serous\\n- Mucinous\\n- Endometrioid","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Gynecologic Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Gynecologic Oncology","triad":["Serous","Mucinous","Endometrioid"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-head-neck-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Head & Neck Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Head and Neck Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish squamous cell carcinoma from benign/inflammatory lesions, recognize papillary thyroid carcinoma metastases and lymphomas in lymph nodes.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is this head and neck lesion malignant and what is its histologic type? Are margins clear?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish squamous cell carcinoma from benign/inflammatory lesions, recognize papillary thyroid carcinoma metastases and lymphomas in lymph nodes.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Reactive squamous atypia and cystic changes can mimic carcinoma; correlation with clinical and radiologic findings is essential.\\n- Representative Specimens: Mucosal margins, neck dissection lymph nodes, thyroid lobectomy frozen sections.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- SquamousHN\\n- PapillaryThyroid\\n- Lymphoma","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Head and Neck Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Head & Neck Surgery","triad":["SquamousHN","PapillaryThyroid","Lymphoma"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-hepatobiliary-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Liver/Biliary Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Hepatobiliary Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Differentiate primary hepatocellular patterns from metastatic tumors and benign regenerative nodules; assess bile duct lesions for malignancy.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is this hepatic or bile duct lesion malignant and are surgical margins free of tumor?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Differentiate primary hepatocellular patterns from metastatic tumors and benign regenerative nodules; assess bile duct lesions for malignancy.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Poorly differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma may mimic cholangiocarcinoma; correlation with radiology and immunostains on permanents is essential.\\n- Representative Specimens: Segmental hepatectomy margins, wedge biopsies of hepatic nodules, bile duct excisions.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Hepatocellular\\n- Cholangiocarcinoma\\n- MetastaticLiver","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Hepatobiliary Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Hepatobiliary Surgery","triad":["Hepatocellular","Cholangiocarcinoma","MetastaticLiver"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-neuropathology","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Neuropathology: Core Principles","category":"Neuropathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Provide rapid classification of CNS lesions into glioma, metastatic tumor, or meningioma to guide extent of surgery.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: What is the nature of this central nervous system lesion and does it require further resection?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Provide rapid classification of CNS lesions into glioma, metastatic tumor, or meningioma to guide extent of surgery.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Frozen sections distort brain tissue; cytologic crush preparations may be more reliable for grading glial tumors.\\n- Representative Specimens: Stereotactic biopsies, intraoperative tumor debulking specimens.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Glioma\\n- MetastasisCNS\\n- Meningioma","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Neuropathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Neuropathology","triad":["Glioma","MetastasisCNS","Meningioma"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-pancreatic-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Pancreas Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Pancreatic Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish inflammation and benign cystic lesions from invasive carcinoma; evaluate margins for tumor.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is the pancreatic resection margin free of invasive carcinoma and is this lesion malignant or benign?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish inflammation and benign cystic lesions from invasive carcinoma; evaluate margins for tumor.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Desmoplastic stroma can mimic chronic pancreatitis on frozen; caution with diagnosing adenocarcinoma without definitive glands invading stroma.\\n- Representative Specimens: Pancreatic neck margin from Whipple procedure, distal pancreatectomy margins, enucleation of cystic lesions.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Glandular\\n- Ductal\\n- Desmoplastic","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Pancreatic Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Pancreatic Surgery","triad":["Glandular","Ductal","Desmoplastic"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-thoracic-surgery","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Lung Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Thoracic Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Provide rapid triage for malignancy versus benign/reactive lesions; do not overinterpret frozen artifacts.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is this lung lesion malignant and, if so, should more lung tissue be resected?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Provide rapid triage for malignancy versus benign/reactive lesions; do not overinterpret frozen artifacts.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Many subtle adenocarcinoma patterns (e.g. lepidic) are under‑diagnosed on frozen; deferral may be appropriate.\\n- Representative Specimens: Wedge resections for peripheral nodules, mediastinal lymph node biopsies, lobectomies.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- Adenocarcinoma\\n- Squamous\\n- SmallCell","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Thoracic Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Thoracic Surgery","triad":["Adenocarcinoma","Squamous","SmallCell"],"keyPointCount":4}},{"id":"ioc-overview-urologic-oncology","sourceRepo":"ioc-next-app","sourcePath":"src/content/downloads_imports/raw/ioc_overviews.raw.json","contentType":"lecture","title":"Renal Pathology: Core Principles","category":"Genitourinary Pathology","summary":"Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish clear cell renal cell carcinoma from oncocytoma and other benign lesions; evaluate partial nephrectomy margins.","body":"## Key Points\\n- Core Teaching Question: Is the renal mass malignant, and if so, what subtype is it; are margins free of tumor?\\n- Primary Diagnostic Focus: Distinguish clear cell renal cell carcinoma from oncocytoma and other benign lesions; evaluate partial nephrectomy margins.\\n- Cardinal Rule: Papillary and chromophobe renal tumors may appear deceptively bland; rely on architectural patterns more than cytology alone.\\n- Representative Specimens: Partial nephrectomy margins, radical nephrectomy sampling, ureteral margins.\\n\\n## Triad Summary\\n- ClearCell\\n- PapillaryKidney\\n- Chromophobe","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Genitourinary Pathology","didactic"],"provenance":{"sourceServiceLine":"Urologic Oncology","triad":["ClearCell","PapillaryKidney","Chromophobe"],"keyPointCount":4}}]`),i=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"st-soft-tissue-spindle-basic","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Spindle Cell Tumor Workup (Soft Tissue)","category":"Soft Tissue","summary":"A minimal, type-valid pathway: start → morphology gate → decision → result.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Soft Tissue"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"n1","nodeCount":9,"nodes":{"n1":{"id":"n1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Review clinical context (age, site, depth), imaging, and gross. Confirm this is a spindle cell predominant lesion on H&E.","options":[{"label":"Proceed to morphology gate","nextNodeId":"n2"}]},"n2":{"id":"n2","type":"morphology_gate","title":"Morphology gate","description":"Confirm key pattern-level features before ordering broad panels.","morphologyFeatures":["Spindle cell predominant","Growth pattern: fascicular / storiform / patternless / herringbone","Stroma: collagenized / myxoid / hyalinized","Vascular pattern: staghorn / branching / delicate capillaries","Necrosis / mitotic activity / atypia"],"recommendedInitialIHC":["AE1/AE3","S100","SOX10","SMA","Desmin","CD34"],"options":[{"label":"Patternless + staghorn vessels (consider SFT)","nextNodeId":"n3","rationale":"Classic architectural clue for SFT spectrum."},{"label":"Fascicular + eosinophilic cytoplasm (consider SMC)","nextNodeId":"n4","rationale":"Smooth muscle morphology suggests SMA/Desmin."},{"label":"Wavy nuclei / nerve association (consider PNST)","nextNodeId":"n5","rationale":"PNST clues push S100/SOX10."}]},"n3":{"id":"n3","type":"decision","title":"Decision: SFT pathway","description":"If SFT is suspected, confirm with lineage-defining markers and exclude mimics.","recommendedReflexIHC":["STAT6","CD34","BCL2","CD99"],"molecularIndications":["NAB2-STAT6 fusion testing if STAT6 equivocal or for challenging cases"],"options":[{"label":"Confirm SFT","nextNodeId":"n6"},{"label":"Not SFT / equivocal","nextNodeId":"n7"}]},"n4":{"id":"n4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: Smooth muscle pathway","description":"Confirm smooth muscle differentiation and assess malignancy parameters.","recommendedReflexIHC":["SMA","Desmin","H-caldesmon"],"options":[{"label":"Confirm smooth muscle tumor","nextNodeId":"n8"},{"label":"Equivocal smooth muscle","nextNodeId":"n7"}]},"n5":{"id":"n5","type":"decision","title":"Decision: PNST pathway","description":"Confirm neural crest differentiation and consider site-specific entities.","recommendedReflexIHC":["S100","SOX10","EMA","Claudin-1","GLUT1"],"options":[{"label":"Confirm PNST","nextNodeId":"n9"},{"label":"Not PNST / equivocal","nextNodeId":"n7"}]},"n6":{"id":"n6","type":"result","title":"Result: Solitary fibrous tumor favored","description":"Integrate morphology + STAT6 nuclear positivity. Risk stratify by size, mitoses, necrosis, and age as applicable.","diagnosis":"Solitary fibrous tumor","confirmatoryStudies":["STAT6 (nuclear)","Consider fusion testing if STAT6 negative/equivocal"],"pearls":["Patternless architecture + staghorn vasculature is a strong clue.","STAT6 is the key confirmatory marker."],"pitfalls":["CD34 is supportive but not specific.","Beware cellular SFT vs other hypercellular spindle tumors."],"prognosis":"Variable; risk stratification recommended."},"n7":{"id":"n7","type":"stop","title":"Stop: broaden differential","description":"If lineage is unclear, stop and broaden workup (consider keratin-positive sarcomatoid carcinoma, melanoma, synovial sarcoma, MPNST, etc.). Use targeted panels and correlate with imaging/gross.","stopConditions":["Unexpected keratin positivity","Strong SOX10 with atypical morphology","Discrepant clinical/radiologic scenario"]},"n8":{"id":"n8","type":"result","title":"Result: Smooth muscle tumor favored","description":"If SMA/Desmin/H-caldesmon support SMC differentiation, classify based on site and malignant criteria.","diagnosis":"Smooth muscle tumor (site-specific classification required)","confirmatoryStudies":["SMA","Desmin","H-caldesmon"],"pearls":["Fascicles + blunt-ended nuclei + eosinophilic cytoplasm support SMC."],"pitfalls":["Myofibroblastic lesions can be SMA+ but desmin/H-caldesmon-."]},"n9":{"id":"n9","type":"result","title":"Result: PNST favored","description":"If S100/SOX10 support neural differentiation, subclassify with clinicopathologic correlation and consider perineurial markers as appropriate.","diagnosis":"Peripheral nerve sheath tumor (subclassify)","confirmatoryStudies":["S100","SOX10","EMA/Claudin-1/GLUT1 if perineurial differentiation suspected"],"pearls":["SOX10 is often more specific for Schwannian differentiation than S100 alone."],"pitfalls":["Melanocytic lesions can mimic PNST and share SOX10 positivity."]}}}},{"id":"bone-giant-cell-basic","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Lytic Bone Lesion: Giant Cell–Rich Differential","category":"Bone","summary":"Minimal pathway for giant cell–rich lytic bone lesions: start → decision → result/stop.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Bone"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"b1","nodeCount":5,"nodes":{"b1":{"id":"b1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Confirm radiology: lytic vs sclerotic, epiphyseal vs metaphyseal, and patient age. Review H&E for giant cell–rich pattern.","options":[{"label":"Proceed to decision node","nextNodeId":"b2"}]},"b2":{"id":"b2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: giant cell–rich patterns","description":"Use radiology + distribution of osteoclast-type giant cells and stromal cytology.","options":[{"label":"Epiphyseal lesion in skeletally mature, uniform giant cells","nextNodeId":"b3"},{"label":"Aneurysmal spaces / blood-filled cystic change","nextNodeId":"b4"},{"label":"High-grade atypia / malignant osteoid","nextNodeId":"b5"}]},"b3":{"id":"b3","type":"result","title":"Result: Giant cell tumor of bone favored","description":"Correlate with epiphyseal location; consider H3F3A (G34) mutation testing if needed.","diagnosis":"Giant cell tumor of bone","confirmatoryStudies":["H3F3A mutation testing (as needed)"],"pearls":["Mononuclear stromal cells are the neoplastic population."],"pitfalls":["Beware giant cell–rich osteosarcoma if malignant osteoid present."]},"b4":{"id":"b4","type":"result","title":"Result: Aneurysmal bone cyst pattern","description":"Primary ABC can show USP6 rearrangement; secondary ABC occurs over other lesions.","diagnosis":"Aneurysmal bone cyst (primary vs secondary)","confirmatoryStudies":["USP6 rearrangement testing if primary ABC suspected"],"pearls":["Always exclude underlying lesion in secondary ABC."],"pitfalls":["Telangiectatic osteosarcoma can mimic ABC radiologically and grossly."]},"b5":{"id":"b5","type":"stop","title":"Stop: consider aggressive/malignant bone tumor","description":"If malignant osteoid or marked atypia is present, stop and evaluate for osteosarcoma subtype (including telangiectatic) with full radiologic correlation and sampling.","stopConditions":["Malignant lace-like osteoid","Marked nuclear pleomorphism in stromal cells","Atypical mitoses"]}}}},{"id":"cp-mi-qc-failure-response","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"QC Failure Response","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Operational triage for a QC failure: characterize the control pattern, protect patient reporting, and choose the next corrective action.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["qc failure","quality control failure","qc troubleshooting"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"q1","nodeCount":7,"nodes":{"q1":{"id":"q1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Pause auto-release for the affected assay or bench, confirm which control level failed, and review the most recent Levey-Jennings pattern before touching patient samples.","options":[{"label":"Characterize the QC signal","nextNodeId":"q2"}]},"q2":{"id":"q2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: characterize the QC signal","description":"Separate isolated random-error patterns from systematic failure and post-change instability.","options":[{"label":"Single control point outside limits without a broader pattern","nextNodeId":"q3","rationale":"A lone miss may reflect random error, but patient reporting still stays on hold until you verify the run."},{"label":"Shift, trend, or multirule violation across levels or runs","nextNodeId":"q4","rationale":"This pattern is more consistent with systematic error and needs broader containment."},{"label":"Failure appeared after calibration, reagent lot change, or maintenance","nextNodeId":"q5","rationale":"Post-change instability often needs verification logic before routine testing resumes."}]},"q3":{"id":"q3","type":"result","title":"Result: random-error check with reporting hold","description":"Repeat the affected control level, inspect preparation and instrument handling, and resume patient testing only after the rerun is acceptable.","confirmatoryStudies":["Repeat control material at the failed level","Review recent Levey-Jennings position for the same level"],"pearls":["A single isolated miss is not a free pass to release patient results.","Random-error thinking still starts with containment."],"pitfalls":["Do not ignore a failed control because one other level remained in range.","Do not rerun patient samples before the control problem is resolved."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Levey-Jennings QC Studio"},"q4":{"id":"q4","type":"result","title":"Result: systematic-error response","description":"Treat the event as a probable method or instrument problem, broaden the hold, and use rule-based troubleshooting before restarting the assay.","confirmatoryStudies":["Review Westgard rule pattern across all affected control levels","Inspect calibration status, reagent integrity, and recent maintenance events"],"pearls":["Shift and trend patterns matter more than any single point.","A multirule event is an assay-process problem until proven otherwise."],"pitfalls":["Do not correct a systematic problem by repeated blind reruns.","Do not restart patient reporting without documenting the corrective action."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Westgard Rules Studio"},"q5":{"id":"q5","type":"decision","title":"Decision: post-change instability","description":"If the failure followed a method change event, decide whether the problem is already patient-facing or still confined to verification work.","options":[{"label":"Patient results may already be affected or the assay is safety-critical","nextNodeId":"q6","rationale":"Escalation and communication come before routine restart."},{"label":"No patient reporting yet; the issue is contained within startup verification","nextNodeId":"q7","rationale":"You can stay in verification mode while proving the assay is stable."}]},"q6":{"id":"q6","type":"stop","title":"Stop: protect patients and escalate","description":"Hold affected reporting, notify supervisory leadership, assess whether corrected reports or clinician communication are needed, and document the event as a patient-safety issue.","stopConditions":["Critical-value workflow may be affected","Previously released patient results may be unreliable","The assay cannot be stabilized promptly"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Major Sources of Laboratory Errors Studio"},"q7":{"id":"q7","type":"result","title":"Result: complete verification before restart","description":"Finish the defined verification plan, confirm acceptable control performance after the corrective action, and document restart criteria before patient testing resumes.","confirmatoryStudies":["Verification checks appropriate to the post-change event","Documented restart criteria after corrective action"],"pearls":["Validation and verification are operational decisions, not interchangeable labels.","A stable control recovery needs documented acceptance criteria."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat a post-change QC failure as routine noise.","Do not relabel validation work as verification just to shorten the restart path."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Validation vs Verification Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-mi-validation-verification-triage","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Validation-Versus-Verification Triage","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Choose the right oversight path when a lab is bringing on a test, modifying an assay, or restarting a changed method.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["validation vs verification","validation verification triage","verification pathway"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"v1","nodeCount":5,"nodes":{"v1":{"id":"v1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Define what changed before choosing the oversight frame: a new test claim, a modified method, or a local implementation of an already established method.","options":[{"label":"Classify the implementation scenario","nextNodeId":"v2"}]},"v2":{"id":"v2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what kind of change is this?","description":"Separate truly new or materially altered claims from local confirmation of expected performance.","options":[{"label":"The lab is implementing an established method without materially changing the claim","nextNodeId":"v3","rationale":"This usually favors local verification rather than full validation."},{"label":"The method, specimen use, reportable range, or intended use has materially changed","nextNodeId":"v4","rationale":"A material claim change pushes the oversight path toward validation."},{"label":"The scope of change is still unclear or poorly documented","nextNodeId":"v5","rationale":"You need to stop and define the claim before pretending the oversight path is obvious."}]},"v3":{"id":"v3","type":"result","title":"Result: verification pathway","description":"Use a local verification plan that confirms the method performs as expected in your setting before go-live.","confirmatoryStudies":["Precision, accuracy, and reportable performance checks appropriate to the local implementation","Documented acceptance criteria before release"],"pearls":["Verification confirms expected performance in a local environment.","The claim is not being reinvented; it is being proven locally."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat verification as optional because the method is familiar.","Do not skip documentation just because the assay is already in common use elsewhere."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Validation vs Verification Studio"},"v4":{"id":"v4","type":"result","title":"Result: validation pathway","description":"Use a validation plan when the lab is establishing or materially altering the test claim, then define the studies needed before clinical release.","confirmatoryStudies":["Validation studies matched to the changed claim","Risk-aware review of analytical performance before patient reporting"],"pearls":["A changed claim means the burden of proof is larger than local verification.","Validation is about defending a new or altered use, not just generating paperwork."],"pitfalls":["Do not relabel material method changes as verification to save time.","Do not go live before the altered claim has explicit supporting evidence."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Validation vs Verification Studio"},"v5":{"id":"v5","type":"stop","title":"Stop: define the claim before proceeding","description":"Pause the rollout, clarify intended use and method changes, and document the scope with laboratory leadership before choosing verification or validation.","stopConditions":["Intended use is ambiguous","Method changes are not fully documented","Leadership approval or oversight scope is unresolved"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Major Sources of Laboratory Errors Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-mi-lis-workflow-redesign","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"LIS Workflow Redesign","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Redesign an unsafe reporting workflow by deciding whether interfacing, middleware, or process redesign is the highest-yield safety intervention.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["lis interfacing","workflow redesign","lab information system workflow"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"l1","nodeCount":5,"nodes":{"l1":{"id":"l1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Map the current result path from instrument or source system to the final report, and identify where repeated manual handling occurs.","options":[{"label":"Classify the workflow vulnerability","nextNodeId":"l2"}]},"l2":{"id":"l2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the main workflow failure mode?","description":"Choose the intervention by matching it to the dominant risk rather than defaulting to a favorite informatics tool.","options":[{"label":"Repeated manual transcription or copy-forward between systems","nextNodeId":"l3","rationale":"Structured interfacing is strongest when the recurring risk is transcription or data-transfer error."},{"label":"Rule-based routing, reflexing, or queue management is inconsistent across cases","nextNodeId":"l4","rationale":"Middleware is useful when the safety gain depends on standardized decision logic between systems."},{"label":"The failure is mostly handoff design, staffing, or local process confusion","nextNodeId":"l5","rationale":"Not every unsafe workflow is solved by another software layer."}]},"l3":{"id":"l3","type":"result","title":"Result: interface the workflow","description":"Use LIS or source-system interfacing to remove repeated manual entry and preserve structured result transmission.","confirmatoryStudies":["Map source-to-destination fields and exception handling","Verify that critical result and corrected report paths survive the interface"],"pearls":["An interface is a patient-safety intervention when it removes recurring transcription risk.","Structured connectivity is strongest when the same manual step is repeated at scale."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat manual entry as operationally equivalent to interfacing.","Do not ignore exception-path behavior while celebrating the primary happy path."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: LIS Interfacing Studio"},"l4":{"id":"l4","type":"result","title":"Result: standardize with middleware or rules logic","description":"Use middleware or governed rules logic when the main hazard is inconsistent routing, reflex behavior, or queue prioritization across repeated cases.","confirmatoryStudies":["Documented routing and reflex rules","Validation or verification of rule behavior before clinical use"],"pearls":["Middleware helps when the risk lives in inconsistent operational decisions between systems.","Standardized rules are safer than ad hoc human memory for repetitive pathways."],"pitfalls":["Do not add rules logic without proving the edge cases.","Do not assume middleware fixes a process that was never mapped clearly."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Validation vs Verification Studio"},"l5":{"id":"l5","type":"result","title":"Result: redesign the local process first","description":"Redesign the handoff, staffing, or communication workflow when the main failure is local process design rather than missing software connectivity.","confirmatoryStudies":["Defined ownership for each handoff step","A documented safer-state workflow before reintroducing automation"],"pearls":["A bad process wrapped in software is still a bad process.","Workflow clarity is often the first safety intervention."],"pitfalls":["Do not buy informatics complexity to avoid naming the real process flaw.","Do not leave corrected-report or critical-value ownership ambiguous."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Major Sources of Laboratory Errors Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-mi-finance-aware-assay-planning","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Finance-Aware Assay Planning","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Plan an assay rollout by balancing break-even logic, acquisition structure, and operational burden before bringing testing in-house.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["assay planning","reagent rental","break even analysis"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"f1","nodeCount":5,"nodes":{"f1":{"id":"f1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Frame the proposed assay around forecasted volume, contribution margin, acquisition structure, and who will absorb the new operational workload.","options":[{"label":"Choose the dominant planning constraint","nextNodeId":"f2"}]},"f2":{"id":"f2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the main planning constraint?","description":"Pick the operational bottleneck before committing to in-house rollout or a platform contract.","options":[{"label":"Projected volume remains below break-even for internalization","nextNodeId":"f3","rationale":"A weak volume forecast is often the clearest reason to delay internal rollout."},{"label":"Volume is plausible, but the acquisition model may hide downstream cost or lock-in","nextNodeId":"f4","rationale":"Reagent-rental and related structures can look attractive until the contract terms are unpacked."},{"label":"The apparent financial win may collapse under staffing, turnaround, or quality burden","nextNodeId":"f5","rationale":"An assay can be mathematically viable and still operationally unsound."}]},"f3":{"id":"f3","type":"result","title":"Result: keep as send-out or defer rollout","description":"If the projected volume remains well below break-even, the safer immediate decision is often to continue send-out testing or delay launch until utilization changes.","confirmatoryStudies":["Break-even calculation using fixed cost and contribution margin","Volume forecast tied to realistic test demand"],"workedExamples":[{"title":"Break-even volume","steps":["Set fixed annual cost at $120,000.","Set reimbursement at $55 per test and variable cost at $15 per test.","Calculate contribution margin: $55 - $15 = $40 per test.","Calculate break-even volume: $120,000 / $40 = 3,000 tests per year.","If projected demand is 1,800 tests per year, the assay remains below break-even."],"takeaway":"A strong reimbursement number does not justify internal rollout when realistic demand remains well below the break-even volume."}],"pearls":["A financially attractive reimbursement rate does not rescue low-volume internalization.","Break-even is an operational decision tool, not just a formula exercise."],"pitfalls":["Do not internalize testing just because the reimbursement looks strong.","Do not ignore fixed cost recovery when judging apparent profitability."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Break-Even Analysis Studio"},"f4":{"id":"f4","type":"result","title":"Result: interrogate the acquisition structure","description":"Compare reagent-rental and direct-purchase logic using total per-reportable-test cost, service obligations, and contract drag before choosing a platform path.","confirmatoryStudies":["Total cost comparison across acquisition models","Review of service, minimum-volume, and reagent-commitment terms"],"workedExamples":[{"title":"Reagent-rental versus direct purchase","steps":["Estimate direct purchase annualized instrument cost at $40,000 and variable reagent cost at $18 per reportable test.","Estimate reagent-rental instrument cost at $0 upfront but variable reagent cost at $28 per reportable test plus a 2,500-test minimum.","At 3,000 tests per year, direct purchase total cost is $40,000 + (3,000 x $18) = $94,000.","At 3,000 tests per year, reagent rental total cost is 3,000 x $28 = $84,000 before service and contract penalties.","Recheck the comparison once service fees, minimum-volume penalties, and reagent commitment clauses are added."],"takeaway":"The cheaper-looking platform on first pass may stop being favorable once contract drag and real utilization are included."}],"pearls":["Reagent rental can reduce upfront capital pressure while increasing downstream operational constraint.","The acquisition model matters because it changes the real cost of each reportable result."],"pitfalls":["Do not assume reagent rental is automatically the low-risk option.","Do not compare platforms without looking at the contract terms that shape real utilization."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Reagent Rental Decision Studio"},"f5":{"id":"f5","type":"result","title":"Result: stop for operational capacity review","description":"Reassess staffing, turnaround expectations, and quality burden before rollout when the hidden constraint is workforce or process capacity rather than purchase price alone.","confirmatoryStudies":["Staffing and throughput review for the affected section","Turnaround-time and quality-risk assessment for the proposed workflow"],"pearls":["A mathematically favorable assay can still fail if the section cannot absorb it safely.","Productivity metrics need quality and turnaround context to be meaningful."],"pitfalls":["Do not use raw volume as the only proxy for readiness.","Do not call a rollout efficient if it depends on fragile staffing workarounds."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Staff Productivity Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-foundations-anemia-workup","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Anemia Workup and Hemolysis Triage","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Use CBC indices, reticulocyte response, and hemolysis cues to decide whether anemia reflects blood loss or hemolysis, reduced production, or urgent marrow pathology.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["anemia workup","hemolysis triage","red cell triage"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"a1","nodeCount":7,"nodes":{"a1":{"id":"a1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Begin with hemoglobin, MCV, reticulocyte response, smear clues, and whether other blood cell lines are also abnormal.","options":[{"label":"Classify the anemia frame","nextNodeId":"a2"}]},"a2":{"id":"a2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the first diagnostic frame?","description":"Separate increased red-cell loss from impaired production and from patterns that need urgent marrow-level escalation.","options":[{"label":"Reticulocytes are appropriately elevated or hemolysis or blood-loss clues are present","nextNodeId":"a3","rationale":"A brisk marrow response pushes the differential toward red-cell loss rather than failure to produce."},{"label":"Reticulocytes are low or inappropriately normal, suggesting a production problem","nextNodeId":"a4","rationale":"Poor marrow response reframes the workup around iron, nutrient, kidney, endocrine, inflammatory, or marrow causes."},{"label":"Additional cytopenias, circulating blasts, or marked smear dysplasia raise concern for marrow pathology","nextNodeId":"a5","rationale":"This pattern should not be flattened into routine outpatient anemia workup."}]},"a3":{"id":"a3","type":"result","title":"Result: hemolysis or blood-loss pathway","description":"Confirm whether the elevated reticulocyte response reflects hemolysis or active blood loss, then choose targeted follow-up studies rather than broad screening.","confirmatoryStudies":["Reticulocyte count with smear review","LDH, indirect bilirubin, and haptoglobin","DAT when immune hemolysis is plausible"],"pearls":["Reticulocytosis is a physiologic clue, not the final diagnosis.","DAT belongs in the hemolysis branch, not the default anemia screen."],"pitfalls":["Do not call anemia hypoproliferative when the reticulocyte response is clearly brisk.","Do not miss immune hemolysis when the smear and chemistry pattern already support red-cell destruction."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio"},"a4":{"id":"a4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what kind of production problem is most likely?","description":"Use indices and context to distinguish iron-restricted states from macrocytic or marrow-linked patterns.","options":[{"label":"Microcytosis or iron-restricted physiology is most likely","nextNodeId":"a6","rationale":"Iron deficiency, inflammation, and related states stay near the top when the indices point that way."},{"label":"Macrocytosis, multilineage abnormalities, or renal or endocrine context changes the frame","nextNodeId":"a7","rationale":"Macrocytic and broader cytopenic patterns often need nutrient, systemic, or marrow-level reasoning."}]},"a5":{"id":"a5","type":"stop","title":"Stop: urgent marrow or hematopathology escalation","description":"Pause routine anemia sorting and escalate when blasts, pancytopenia, or strong dysplasia suggest a marrow-centered process that needs same-day hematopathology reasoning.","stopConditions":["Blasts or highly suspicious immature forms on smear","Pancytopenia or multilineage failure pattern","Marked dysplasia or other concern for acute leukemia or marrow infiltration"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Flow Cytometry and Hematopathology Studio"},"a6":{"id":"a6","type":"result","title":"Result: iron-restricted or microcytic production pathway","description":"Use iron studies and clinical context to decide whether the anemia reflects true iron deficiency, inflammatory restriction, or a less common microcytic disorder.","confirmatoryStudies":["Ferritin and transferrin saturation or iron studies","Peripheral smear review for microcytic morphology","Targeted hemoglobinopathy testing when history or indices support it"],"pearls":["Low MCV narrows the frame, but ferritin and context still matter.","Microcytosis is a routing clue, not proof of one single diagnosis."],"pitfalls":["Do not collapse all microcytic anemia into iron deficiency without iron studies.","Do not forget that inflammation can mimic iron deficiency in the lab pattern."]},"a7":{"id":"a7","type":"result","title":"Result: macrocytic or marrow-linked production pathway","description":"Check nutrient, renal, endocrine, medication, and marrow-linked causes when the anemia pattern is macrocytic or broader than isolated iron restriction.","confirmatoryStudies":["B12 and folate assessment when clinically appropriate","Renal or endocrine context review with chemistry correlation","Marrow-directed evaluation if cytopenias or dysplasia persist"],"pearls":["Macrocytosis broadens the workup beyond simple iron logic.","Production failure that involves more than one cell line deserves a marrow-level frame."],"pitfalls":["Do not stop at MCV without looking at the rest of the CBC and smear.","Do not defer marrow escalation when persistent cytopenias and dysplasia are already visible."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Flow Cytometry and Hematopathology Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-foundations-bleeding-diatathesis-triage","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Bleeding Diathesis and Coagulation Test Interpretation","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Use bleeding pattern, platelet data, and coagulation screening tests to decide whether the problem is primary hemostasis, factor pathway dysfunction, or unstable systemic coagulopathy.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["bleeding diathesis triage","coagulation test interpretation","hemostasis triage"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"b1","nodeCount":7,"nodes":{"b1":{"id":"b1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Anchor the workup in the bleeding pattern, medication history, platelet count, and initial PT, aPTT, fibrinogen, and smear context.","options":[{"label":"Classify the hemostatic problem","nextNodeId":"b2"}]},"b2":{"id":"b2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: where does the pattern point first?","description":"Distinguish platelet or von Willebrand-type bleeding from factor pathway problems and unstable systemic coagulopathy.","options":[{"label":"Mucocutaneous bleeding, platelet abnormalities, or von Willebrand-type pattern","nextNodeId":"b3","rationale":"Primary hemostasis problems usually declare themselves through the bleeding pattern before factor studies solve the case."},{"label":"PT or aPTT abnormalities suggest a factor pathway or inhibitor problem","nextNodeId":"b4","rationale":"Screening tests now become the main routing tool."},{"label":"Active or unstable bleeding with broad coagulopathy concern","nextNodeId":"b5","rationale":"When the patient is unstable, triage and support move faster than elegant diagnostic sequencing."}]},"b3":{"id":"b3","type":"result","title":"Result: primary hemostasis pathway","description":"Prioritize platelet count and smear review, medication exposure, and von Willebrand testing when the pattern fits primary hemostasis rather than coagulation-factor deficiency.","confirmatoryStudies":["Platelet count with peripheral smear review","von Willebrand antigen and activity testing when indicated","Medication and qualitative platelet dysfunction review"],"pearls":["The bleeding pattern matters as much as the screening numbers.","Normal PT and aPTT do not exclude clinically important platelet or von Willebrand disorders."],"pitfalls":["Do not order factor cascades first when the history already points to primary hemostasis.","Do not ignore medication-related platelet dysfunction."]},"b4":{"id":"b4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what do the screening tests imply?","description":"Use the PT and aPTT pattern to separate intrinsic-pathway issues from broader consumptive or multifactor abnormalities.","options":[{"label":"Isolated aPTT abnormality or targeted factor or inhibitor question","nextNodeId":"b6","rationale":"A focused intrinsic-pathway problem often needs mixing-study logic and factor-directed follow-up."},{"label":"Multiple screening tests are abnormal or fibrinogen is low","nextNodeId":"b7","rationale":"Combined abnormalities broaden the frame toward systemic coagulopathy."}]},"b5":{"id":"b5","type":"stop","title":"Stop: unstable bleeding or systemic coagulopathy response","description":"Escalate immediately when the patient has unstable bleeding, suspected DIC, severe liver-related coagulopathy, or a situation where supportive transfusion decisions cannot wait.","stopConditions":["Hemodynamic instability or major active bleeding","Possible DIC or severe multifactor coagulopathy","Immediate component-support decisions are required"]},"b6":{"id":"b6","type":"result","title":"Result: factor deficiency or inhibitor pathway","description":"Use mixing-study logic and targeted factor evaluation when the main clue is an isolated aPTT or a narrower factor-pathway problem.","confirmatoryStudies":["Mixing study when appropriate","Targeted factor assays or inhibitor evaluation","Clinical review for anticoagulant exposure"],"pearls":["An isolated screening-test abnormality should narrow the follow-up rather than trigger indiscriminate testing.","Mixing studies answer a routing question: deficiency versus inhibitor."],"pitfalls":["Do not interpret an abnormal aPTT without considering anticoagulant effect.","Do not skip targeted follow-up once the screening pattern is already focused."]},"b7":{"id":"b7","type":"result","title":"Result: consumptive or multifactor coagulopathy pathway","description":"Broaden the frame to DIC, liver-related dysfunction, dilutional states, or other multifactor causes when several screening studies move together.","confirmatoryStudies":["Fibrinogen and broader coagulation-panel correlation","Clinical review for DIC, liver dysfunction, massive transfusion, or anticoagulant exposure","Supportive transfusion planning when clinically indicated"],"pearls":["Multiple abnormal screening tests usually mean the problem is larger than a single factor deficiency.","The clinical context decides whether the next step is diagnosis, support, or both."],"pitfalls":["Do not force a single-factor explanation onto a global coagulopathy pattern.","Do not separate coagulation interpretation from the severity of active bleeding."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-foundations-specimen-to-result-workflow","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Specimen-to-Result CP Workflow","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Move a Clinical Pathology request from specimen quality triage and specimen integrity through bench selection, result interpretation, and safe reporting without skipping preanalytic or postanalytic safeguards.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["specimen to result workflow","critical reporting workflow","bench selection workflow"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"s1","nodeCount":8,"nodes":{"s1":{"id":"s1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Confirm patient identity, specimen integrity, and the clinical question before choosing a bench pathway or releasing any result.","options":[{"label":"Check whether the specimen is fit for use","nextNodeId":"s2"}]},"s2":{"id":"s2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is the specimen usable for the requested question?","description":"A flawed specimen should redirect the workflow before deeper bench reasoning begins.","options":[{"label":"Misidentification, contamination, or collection-quality problems make the sample unsafe","nextNodeId":"s3","rationale":"Preanalytic failure is still the highest-yield finding when the specimen itself is compromised."},{"label":"The specimen is acceptable, but the next step depends on the testing lane","nextNodeId":"s4","rationale":"Once integrity is acceptable, the question becomes which CP branch should own the workup."}]},"s3":{"id":"s3","type":"stop","title":"Stop: recollect or correct before testing","description":"Do not push a bad specimen through the lab. Resolve identity or collection issues, communicate the problem, and recollect when needed.","stopConditions":["Identity mismatch or unlabeled specimen","Collection or contamination problem invalidates interpretation","The specimen quality makes downstream testing misleading"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: Major Sources of Laboratory Errors Studio"},"s4":{"id":"s4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: which CP lane owns the next action?","description":"Route the specimen into the branch where the main interpretive or safety question actually lives.","options":[{"label":"Culture setup, organism workup, or susceptibility logic is central","nextNodeId":"s5","rationale":"Microbiology workflow depends on specimen quality, media strategy, and AST consequences."},{"label":"Chemistry or endocrine interpretation and critical-result management are central","nextNodeId":"s6","rationale":"Chemistry workups often pivot on analyte interpretation and method-aware critical reporting."},{"label":"Identity-sensitive blood bank or hemolysis-related reasoning is central","nextNodeId":"s7","rationale":"Transfusion and DAT-linked problems should stay inside their safety-sensitive workflow."},{"label":"The weak point is the interface, handoff, or reporting chain itself","nextNodeId":"s8","rationale":"Sometimes the specimen is fine and the danger lives in the workflow."}]},"s5":{"id":"s5","type":"result","title":"Result: microbiology bench workflow","description":"Proceed through specimen-quality review, organism workup, and AST interpretation when microbiology owns the main diagnostic and reporting task.","confirmatoryStudies":["Specimen-quality assessment before deep interpretation","Bench identification pathway matched to organism class","AST interpretation tied to stewardship and reporting consequences"],"pearls":["Microbiology workflow begins with specimen quality, not just the organism result.","AST categories matter because they change downstream treatment and communication."],"pitfalls":["Do not over-interpret a poor specimen.","Do not separate AST interpretation from organism identity and reporting consequence."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio"},"s6":{"id":"s6","type":"result","title":"Result: chemistry interpretation and critical-result path","description":"Use chemistry or endocrine interpretation logic when the central problem is analyte meaning, method consequence, or critical-value management.","confirmatoryStudies":["Context-aware analyte interpretation","Method or specimen considerations that change result trust","Critical-result escalation when clinically required"],"pearls":["A chemistry result is only useful when you trust both the specimen and the method context.","Critical-result communication is part of the workflow, not an afterthought."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat chemistry interpretation as detached from specimen or method quality.","Do not release a critical result without the appropriate communication pathway."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Chemical Pathology Endocrine and Metabolic Studio"},"s7":{"id":"s7","type":"result","title":"Result: transfusion or hemolysis-sensitive pathway","description":"Keep identity-sensitive compatibility and hemolysis workups inside blood bank or DAT-guided reasoning when the risk of wrong-patient or reaction harm is central.","confirmatoryStudies":["Identity and compatibility review","DAT-linked hemolysis workup when clinically indicated","Transfusion-safety communication for urgent events"],"pearls":["Blood bank workflow is safety-first because the specimen identity burden is unusually high.","Hemolysis questions change rapidly when transfusion exposure is part of the history."],"pitfalls":["Do not flatten blood bank problems into generic chemistry or hematology workflows.","Do not ignore identity-sensitive safeguards when compatibility questions are in play."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio"},"s8":{"id":"s8","type":"result","title":"Result: workflow or reporting redesign pathway","description":"Address interface, middleware, or handoff weakness when the specimen and bench work are sound but the reporting chain is still unsafe.","confirmatoryStudies":["Map the manual handoff or interface vulnerability","Decide whether redesign, interfacing, or middleware is the highest-yield fix","Document the reporting risk being reduced"],"pearls":["A technically correct result can still become unsafe in the reporting chain.","Workflow repair belongs in the CP reasoning surface because it changes patient safety."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat postanalytic risk as less important than bench accuracy.","Do not patch a systemic reporting weakness with repeated manual workarounds."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Management and Informatics: LIS Interfacing Studio"}}}},{"id":"cp-transfusion-reaction-triage","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Transfusion Reaction Triage","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Use immediate symptom pattern, transfusion-safety steps, and blood-bank reasoning to separate hemolytic, febrile or allergic, and pulmonary or volume-overload transfusion reactions.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["transfusion reaction workup","hemolytic transfusion reaction","trali taco transfusion reactions"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"tr1","nodeCount":8,"nodes":{"tr1":{"id":"tr1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Begin when new symptoms arise during or shortly after transfusion and frame the event first as a transfusion-safety problem rather than a generic anemia or chemistry question.","options":[{"label":"Classify the reaction pattern and immediate safety risk","nextNodeId":"tr2"}]},"tr2":{"id":"tr2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is this an active transfusion-safety event?","description":"Treat fever, chills, dyspnea, hypotension, flank pain, dark urine, urticaria, or rapid cardiopulmonary change during or after transfusion as a true reaction pathway until proven otherwise.","options":[{"label":"Symptoms developed during or soon after transfusion and could reflect reaction harm","nextNodeId":"tr3","rationale":"Wrong-patient exposure, hemolysis, pulmonary injury, and severe hypersensitivity must be contained before deeper classification."},{"label":"The pattern is not convincingly linked to transfusion timing or safety risk","nextNodeId":"tr8","rationale":"If the event does not behave like a transfusion reaction, do not force it into blood-bank triage."}]},"tr3":{"id":"tr3","type":"stop","title":"Stop: stop transfusion and escalate immediately","description":"Stop the transfusion, maintain IV access, notify the blood bank and clinical team, and begin clerical and specimen-identity review before pursuing detailed classification.","stopConditions":["Possible hemolysis, hypotension, or respiratory compromise","Identity-sensitive blood-bank harm cannot be excluded","A reaction workup must begin before routine product continuation"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Hazards of Transfusion"},"tr4":{"id":"tr4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the dominant reaction pattern?","description":"After the transfusion is stopped and the event is escalated, separate hemolytic patterns from febrile or allergic reactions and from respiratory or volume-overload hazards.","options":[{"label":"Fever, chills, flank pain, dark urine, hemolysis labs, or compatibility-error clues dominate","nextNodeId":"tr5","rationale":"This pattern needs immediate blood-bank and DAT-linked reasoning."},{"label":"Urticaria, pruritus, fever, or anaphylactoid features dominate without clear hemolysis","nextNodeId":"tr6","rationale":"This favors febrile nonhemolytic, allergic, or anaphylactic reaction pathways."},{"label":"Dyspnea, hypoxemia, pulmonary edema, or circulatory-overload features dominate","nextNodeId":"tr7","rationale":"TRALI and TACO have immediate patient-safety consequences that outrun serologic detail."}]},"tr5":{"id":"tr5","type":"result","title":"Result: hemolytic transfusion reaction workup","description":"Proceed through clerical check, repeat blood-bank compatibility review, hemolysis assessment, and DAT or eluate logic when immune hemolysis is plausible.","confirmatoryStudies":["Clerical and patient-unit identity check","Repeat ABO/Rh or compatibility review as indicated","Hemolysis assessment with DAT-linked workup when clinically indicated"],"pearls":["DAT is a workup tool inside a broader transfusion-reaction pathway, not the whole diagnosis.","Identity review belongs early because wrong-patient harm changes everything."],"pitfalls":["Do not continue classification while the transfusion is still running.","Do not treat a positive DAT as a complete answer without hemolysis and compatibility context."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio"},"tr6":{"id":"tr6","type":"result","title":"Result: febrile, allergic, or anaphylactic reaction pathway","description":"Reframe the event around febrile nonhemolytic, allergic, or anaphylactic reaction logic and choose the next safest blood-bank and clinical response.","confirmatoryStudies":["Reaction-pattern review without overcalling hemolysis","Clinical correlation for allergic versus febrile versus anaphylactic features","Blood-bank documentation and product-safety follow-up"],"pearls":["Not every transfusion reaction is hemolytic, but every real reaction still needs structured safety handling.","The main task is safe classification plus the right immediate response."],"pitfalls":["Do not default every fever to acute hemolysis.","Do not dismiss severe allergic or anaphylactic patterns as minor reactions."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Febrile, Allergic, and Anaphylactic Reactions"},"tr7":{"id":"tr7","type":"result","title":"Result: pulmonary or circulatory hazard pathway","description":"Differentiate TRALI from TACO when respiratory decompensation or overload signs dominate and escalate because the patient-safety consequence is immediate.","confirmatoryStudies":["Clinical assessment of respiratory timing and volume status","Transfusion history and product context","Blood-bank documentation with urgent clinical communication"],"pearls":["TRALI and TACO are safety-first classifications before they are board-style vocabulary items.","Respiratory deterioration after transfusion should stay in the transfusion-hazard lane."],"pitfalls":["Do not collapse pulmonary transfusion hazards into a generic cardiopulmonary differential.","Do not delay escalation while waiting for perfect subtype certainty."],"relatedTutorialQuery":"Transfusion-Related Acute Lung Injury (TRALI)"},"tr8":{"id":"tr8","type":"stop","title":"Stop: route away from transfusion-reaction triage","description":"If transfusion timing, symptom pattern, and safety context do not support a true reaction pathway, leave this lane and return to the broader CP workup that best fits the case.","stopConditions":["No convincing transfusion-linked temporal relationship","Symptoms are better explained by a non-transfusion process","Identity-sensitive blood-bank harm is not the central risk"],"relatedTutorialQuery":"blood banking transfusion medicine"}}}},{"id":"cp-transfusion-crossmatch-workup","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Crossmatch Workup","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Stepwise blood-bank algorithm for crossmatch incompatibility, specimen identification checks, antibody-screen correlation, and safe unit-selection escalation.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["compatibility workup","alloantibody workup","transfusion compatibility"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"cx1","nodeCount":8,"nodes":{"cx1":{"id":"cx1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"A red-cell unit request reaches the blood bank with a crossmatch problem, incompatibility concern, or unexpected serologic mismatch.","relatedTutorialQuery":"blood banking transfusion medicine","options":[{"label":"Begin crossmatch workup","nextNodeId":"cx2"}]},"cx2":{"id":"cx2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: active reaction versus routine pretransfusion problem","description":"Decide whether this is a routine compatibility issue or an acute transfusion-safety event requiring immediate reaction workflow.","relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio","options":[{"label":"Active transfusion reaction or new hemolysis concern","nextNodeId":"cx3","rationale":"Route first to immediate safety actions and reaction workup."},{"label":"Routine pretransfusion incompatibility or crossmatch discrepancy","nextNodeId":"cx4","rationale":"Proceed with compatibility-focused serologic workup."}]},"cx3":{"id":"cx3","type":"result","title":"Result: reaction safety path first","description":"Stop transfusion if running, maintain venous access, notify the blood bank and clinical team, perform clerical check, and collect the post-transfusion workup before resuming compatibility logic.","relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio","diagnosis":"Immediate transfusion-safety escalation required","pearls":["Do not continue routine compatibility reasoning before reaction triage.","Clerical error and acute hemolysis must be excluded early."],"pitfalls":["Treating a possible hemolytic reaction as a routine crossmatch nuisance.","Delaying blood-bank notification while chasing serologies."]},"cx4":{"id":"cx4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: specimen identity and ABO/Rh consistency","description":"Confirm patient and sample identification, prior blood-bank history, current ABO/Rh typing, and whether the discrepancy is explainable by a clerical or specimen problem.","relatedTutorialQuery":"blood banking transfusion medicine","options":[{"label":"ABO/Rh or identification inconsistency present","nextNodeId":"cx5","rationale":"Possible wrong blood in tube, mislabeled sample, or clerical mismatch."},{"label":"Identity and ABO/Rh are internally consistent","nextNodeId":"cx6","rationale":"Move to antibody-screen and compatibility interpretation."}]},"cx5":{"id":"cx5","type":"stop","title":"Stop: resolve specimen or clerical problem","description":"Hold release, repeat identification checks, obtain a new properly labeled sample if needed, and restart pretransfusion testing only after the identity problem is closed.","relatedTutorialQuery":"blood banking transfusion medicine","stopConditions":["Wrong blood in tube suspected","Sample labeling discrepancy","ABO/Rh mismatch unexplained by known transfusion history"]},"cx6":{"id":"cx6","type":"decision","title":"Decision: antibody-screen or crossmatch pattern","description":"Interpret whether the incompatibility is screen-positive, broad, or DAT or autocontrol-linked, and decide whether the pattern is more consistent with alloantibody, warm autoantibody, or a non-antibody explanation.","relatedTutorialQuery":"red cell immunology and compatibility testing","options":[{"label":"Findings support alloantibody or specific compatibility issue","nextNodeId":"cx7","rationale":"Proceed with antigen-focused compatibility strategy."},{"label":"Broad incompatibility, DAT or autocontrol issue, or recent-transfusion complexity","nextNodeId":"cx8","rationale":"Escalate into DAT-linked or autoantibody-aware workup."}]},"cx7":{"id":"cx7","type":"result","title":"Result: antigen-negative compatible-unit path","description":"Complete panel correlation, select antigen-negative units when indicated, and issue the safest compatible product with documented serologic rationale.","relatedTutorialQuery":"red cell immunology and compatibility testing","diagnosis":"Alloantibody-mediated compatibility workup favored","confirmatoryStudies":["Antibody identification panel","Targeted antigen typing or phenotype correlation"],"pearls":["Compatibility logic should match the specific antibody pattern.","Release should be tied to the safest serologically supportable unit choice."],"pitfalls":["Issuing uncategorized incompatible units before finishing focused antibody reasoning.","Confusing screen positivity with autoantibody by default."]},"cx8":{"id":"cx8","type":"result","title":"Result: DAT-linked or complex compatibility escalation","description":"Use DAT, autocontrol, eluate context, and recent transfusion history to determine whether the safest path is autoantibody-aware selection, specialist escalation, or risk-managed release.","relatedTutorialQuery":"DAT and Hemolytic Transfusion Reaction Studio","diagnosis":"Complex crossmatch discrepancy requiring escalated blood-bank interpretation","confirmatoryStudies":["DAT or autocontrol correlation","Eluate or recent-transfusion contextual workup as indicated"],"pearls":["DAT positivity alone does not prove acute incompatibility.","Recent transfusion can change how broad reactivity is interpreted."],"pitfalls":["Treating every broad incompatibility as an alloantibody problem.","Skipping escalation when safe unit selection remains uncertain."]}}}},{"id":"cp-micro-specimen-quality-triage","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Clinical Microbiology Specimen Quality Triage","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Decide whether a microbiology specimen is acceptable for culture or molecular workup, when recollection is safer, and when a limited bench path can still yield a trustworthy result.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["specimen quality triage","clinical microbiology specimen quality","gram stain specimen triage"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"ms1","nodeCount":7,"nodes":{"ms1":{"id":"ms1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Begin with the specimen itself before focusing on the organism. In microbiology, source quality and transport conditions often determine whether any downstream interpretation is worth trusting.","options":[{"label":"Assess source quality, collection context, and transport integrity","nextNodeId":"ms2"}]},"ms2":{"id":"ms2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is the specimen fit for microbiology interpretation?","description":"Use specimen source, contamination risk, transport delay, and adequacy to decide whether the sample should be worked up, cautiously limited, or rejected.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"Poor source control, heavy contamination risk, or transport failure makes the sample misleading","nextNodeId":"ms3","rationale":"A compromised microbiology specimen should be stopped before the learner overinterprets colonizers or degraded material."},{"label":"The sample is usable, but source quality changes how broad the workup should be","nextNodeId":"ms4","rationale":"Some specimens are acceptable but still require bench restraint and source-aware interpretation."}]},"ms3":{"id":"ms3","type":"stop","title":"Stop: reject or recollect before bench interpretation","description":"Document the quality problem, communicate the limitation, and obtain a better specimen when the current sample cannot support safe microbiology interpretation.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","stopConditions":["Collection quality or contamination risk invalidates interpretation","Transport delay or handling failure undermines organism recovery","Source labeling or specimen adequacy is not trustworthy"]},"ms4":{"id":"ms4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the next safest microbiology bench path?","description":"Once the specimen is usable, choose whether the next move is direct Gram-stain and culture triage, a narrower source-specific bench path, or a molecular-first approach.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"Direct culture and source-aware organism workup are appropriate","nextNodeId":"ms5","rationale":"Good-quality routine specimens can move into organism identification workflow."},{"label":"The sample is usable but high-risk for misleading overgrowth or source ambiguity","nextNodeId":"ms6","rationale":"This lane needs constrained interpretation and explicit contamination awareness."},{"label":"The main value is rapid molecular detection rather than broad culture interpretation","nextNodeId":"ms7","rationale":"Some specimens are best routed toward focused molecular or syndromic testing."}]},"ms5":{"id":"ms5","type":"result","title":"Result: proceed to organism identification workflow","description":"Move the case into morphology, colony, MALDI-TOF, or other organism-identification logic because the specimen quality supports a standard microbiology workup.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Specimen quality supports full microbiology bench interpretation","confirmatoryStudies":["Source-aware culture setup and Gram-stain review","Organism identification pathway matched to the recovered isolate"],"pearls":["Specimen quality is part of the diagnosis because it determines whether an isolate is clinically meaningful.","A strong specimen lets the learner focus on organism reasoning instead of contamination defense."],"pitfalls":["Do not skip source context once growth appears convincing.","Do not separate bench choice from the actual specimen type."]},"ms6":{"id":"ms6","type":"result","title":"Result: limited interpretation with contamination caution","description":"Use a narrower reporting frame when the specimen is usable but vulnerable to colonizer noise, mixed flora confusion, or source-quality limitations.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Specimen quality allows only constrained microbiology interpretation","confirmatoryStudies":["Correlation with source and clinical syndrome","Selective workup of dominant or clearly significant organisms"],"pearls":["Not every usable specimen deserves a maximal workup.","Constrained interpretation is often safer than false precision."],"pitfalls":["Do not overcall mixed or low-quality recovery as true infection.","Do not let bench enthusiasm outrun source credibility."]},"ms7":{"id":"ms7","type":"result","title":"Result: molecular-first or targeted rapid-detection path","description":"Route toward rapid molecular or syndromic testing when specimen quality is adequate and the main clinical value is timely pathogen detection rather than a full conventional culture pathway.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Specimen quality supports targeted rapid microbiology testing","confirmatoryStudies":["Focused molecular assay selection","Correlation with specimen source and expected pathogen class"],"pearls":["A molecular-first path is still governed by specimen quality.","Rapid detection helps most when it answers a clinically urgent question."],"pitfalls":["Do not treat every specimen as equally suited for syndromic testing.","Do not ignore source-quality limitations just because a rapid platform is available."]}}}},{"id":"cp-micro-ast-interpretation","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"AST Interpretation","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Interpret antimicrobial susceptibility results only after organism identity, source context, and reporting consequences are aligned, then decide when to suppress, escalate, or communicate a high-risk result.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["antimicrobial susceptibility testing","susceptibility interpretation","ast stewardship"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"ast1","nodeCount":8,"nodes":{"ast1":{"id":"ast1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Begin AST interpretation only after the organism and source are credible enough that the susceptibility profile will affect real treatment decisions.","options":[{"label":"Frame the isolate, source, and reporting stakes before reading categories","nextNodeId":"ast2"}]},"ast2":{"id":"ast2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is the organism-source pairing trustworthy enough for AST reporting?","description":"Susceptibility categories are only meaningful when the isolate itself is clinically relevant and the specimen source supports treatment-level interpretation.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"The isolate is probably contaminant or source relevance is weak","nextNodeId":"ast3","rationale":"AST can mislead stewardship if the organism should not be driving therapy."},{"label":"The isolate is clinically meaningful and ready for susceptibility interpretation","nextNodeId":"ast4","rationale":"Now the learner can interpret categories in the right clinical frame."}]},"ast3":{"id":"ast3","type":"stop","title":"Stop: do not over-report AST on a weak isolate","description":"Reassess source relevance or recollect rather than pushing susceptibility data that could falsely imply a treatable pathogen.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","stopConditions":["Isolate likely reflects contamination or colonization","Specimen source does not support treatment-driving interpretation","AST reporting would create more confusion than value"]},"ast4":{"id":"ast4","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what kind of AST reporting problem is this?","description":"Separate routine interpretable results from resistant, suppressed, or escalation-worthy patterns before final reporting.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"The profile is straightforward and internally consistent for routine reporting","nextNodeId":"ast5","rationale":"A routine pattern can move into standard source-aware reporting."},{"label":"The profile suggests resistance mechanism, suppression rule, or stewardship-sensitive escalation","nextNodeId":"ast6","rationale":"Complex or high-risk AST patterns need a more deliberate interpretation path."}]},"ast5":{"id":"ast5","type":"result","title":"Result: routine AST reporting path","description":"Report the susceptibility profile in a source-aware way, keeping the organism identity, likely therapy relevance, and local bench conventions aligned.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Routine AST interpretation supports direct reporting","confirmatoryStudies":["AST category review matched to organism identity","Source-aware selection of reportable agents"],"pearls":["AST categories are not free-floating facts; they belong to a specific organism and source.","Routine results still deserve reporting discipline."],"pitfalls":["Do not report every tested drug if the source or organism context makes some misleading.","Do not detach susceptibility categories from the isolate that generated them."]},"ast6":{"id":"ast6","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is this mainly a resistance-pattern problem or a reporting-governance problem?","description":"Some AST cases are hard because the organism is resistant; others are hard because selective suppression or communication rules control what should be released.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"Resistance mechanism or multidrug-resistance concern dominates","nextNodeId":"ast7","rationale":"This needs escalation around resistant phenotype interpretation and stewardship impact."},{"label":"Selective reporting, suppression, or communication rules dominate","nextNodeId":"ast8","rationale":"This needs a reporting-governance frame more than a pure resistance frame."}]},"ast7":{"id":"ast7","type":"result","title":"Result: resistant phenotype escalation path","description":"Escalate when the AST pattern suggests multidrug resistance, discordant phenotype concerns, or a high-stakes treatment implication that should not be treated as routine.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"AST interpretation suggests resistant phenotype requiring higher-level review","confirmatoryStudies":["Phenotype review in light of organism identity","Additional susceptibility or resistance-confirmation workup when indicated","Timely clinical communication for high-risk findings"],"pearls":["High-risk AST patterns are part interpretation problem and part communication problem.","Stewardship consequence is one reason these results matter."],"pitfalls":["Do not bury resistant patterns inside routine release language.","Do not overcall a mechanism without respecting the organism context."]},"ast8":{"id":"ast8","type":"result","title":"Result: selective reporting and stewardship path","description":"Use suppression logic, selective release, and source-aware communication when the main task is deciding what the clinician should actually see and act on.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"AST reporting requires stewardship-aware selective release","confirmatoryStudies":["Review of suppression and selective-reporting policy","Clinical communication of the most actionable agents or restrictions"],"pearls":["Selective AST reporting is a patient-safety and stewardship tool, not just a formatting choice.","What is withheld can matter as much as what is shown."],"pitfalls":["Do not release technically available AST data that undermines stewardship policy.","Do not forget that suppression rules still need clear clinical communication."]}}}},{"id":"cp-micro-organism-identification-workflow","sourceRepo":"stainbrain printable","sourcePath":"src/content/algorithms/algorithms.raw.json","contentType":"algorithm","title":"Organism Identification Workflow","category":"Clinical Pathology","summary":"Choose the next safest organism-identification path by combining Gram stain, growth pattern, source context, and bench method selection before attaching clinical meaning or susceptibility consequences.","body":"","learningObjectives":[],"slides":[],"mcqs":[],"flashcards":[],"references":[],"tags":["Clinical Pathology"],"routeAliases":["microbiology organism identification","maldi tof workflow","gram stain identification"],"provenance":{"startNodeId":"oid1","nodeCount":6,"nodes":{"oid1":{"id":"oid1","type":"start","title":"Start","description":"Begin organism identification only after the specimen is good enough to support microbiology interpretation, then decide which bench signal should drive the next step.","options":[{"label":"Integrate source context with the first bench clues","nextNodeId":"oid2"}]},"oid2":{"id":"oid2","type":"decision","title":"Decision: what is the strongest early identification signal?","description":"Use Gram stain, colony pattern, growth conditions, or rapid platform fit to determine the next identification branch instead of reflexively applying every method.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"Gram stain or colony pattern already narrows the organism class","nextNodeId":"oid3","rationale":"Morphology and growth pattern can often choose the bench path before higher-complexity testing."},{"label":"The isolate needs a faster or more definitive platform-directed identification step","nextNodeId":"oid4","rationale":"Some organisms are best clarified through MALDI-TOF or a targeted rapid method."}]},"oid3":{"id":"oid3","type":"decision","title":"Decision: is the morphology-source pairing coherent?","description":"Decide whether the observed pattern matches a plausible pathogen-source story or whether mixed growth, contamination concern, or unexpected morphology should slow the interpretation.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","options":[{"label":"Pattern is coherent and can proceed through a standard organism workup","nextNodeId":"oid5","rationale":"A consistent early pattern supports a conventional identification branch."},{"label":"Pattern is mixed, unexpected, or contamination-prone","nextNodeId":"oid6","rationale":"Incoherent patterns need restrained interpretation and source re-check before naming the organism."}]},"oid4":{"id":"oid4","type":"result","title":"Result: rapid-platform or targeted identification path","description":"Move to MALDI-TOF, focused biochemical logic, or another targeted rapid method when the next identification step should maximize clarity without unnecessary bench sprawl.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Targeted rapid identification path favored","confirmatoryStudies":["Platform-directed identification matched to organism class","Source-aware correlation before final naming"],"pearls":["The fastest method is useful only when it is the right method for the organism class.","Rapid identification still depends on bench coherence and source logic."],"pitfalls":["Do not choose a platform just because it is available.","Do not let a rapid result outrun source credibility."]},"oid5":{"id":"oid5","type":"result","title":"Result: standard organism workup path","description":"Proceed through a conventional morphology, colony, and focused identification pathway because the early bench pattern and specimen source support a stable organism story.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Standard organism-identification workflow supported","confirmatoryStudies":["Focused morphology and colony review","Follow-on identification matched to the narrowed organism class"],"pearls":["Good organism identification is a sequence of narrowing decisions, not a jump straight to a label.","Source context protects against overreading a plausible-looking isolate."],"pitfalls":["Do not skip the narrowing steps once the broad class is known.","Do not treat every colony as equally clinically meaningful."]},"oid6":{"id":"oid6","type":"result","title":"Result: constrained organism-identification path","description":"Use a limited or cautious identification frame when mixed growth, contamination concern, or source mismatch makes full organism naming unsafe or low-yield.","relatedTutorialQuery":"Clinical Microbiology Methods and AST Studio","diagnosis":"Organism identification requires constrained interpretation","confirmatoryStudies":["Selective follow-up on dominant or source-plausible isolates","Clinical or specimen-quality correlation before final release"],"pearls":["Sometimes the right answer is a restrained workup, not maximal organism naming.","A cautious organism ID path can prevent false downstream AST confidence."],"pitfalls":["Do not force full identification out of mixed or low-trust growth.","Do not separate naming decisions from contamination risk."]}}}}]`),a=[...e,...t,...n].map(e=>({...e,lectureTrack:`curated`,sourceLabel:e.sourceRepo===`didactic_series`?`P@thfndr Local`:`Curated GU Imports`})),o=r.filter(e=>e.sourceRepo===`ioc-next-app`).map(e=>({...e,lectureTrack:`core-principles`,sourceLabel:`Core Principles Series`})),s=[...a,...o];function c(e){return s.find(t=>t.id===e)}export{s as n,i as r,c as t};